# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-missionary-association
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The anti-slavery movement originated during the Age of Enlightenment, focused on ending the transatlantic slave trade.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In Colonial America, a few German Quakers issued the 1688 Germantown Quaker Petition Against Slavery, which marked the beginning of the American abolitionist movement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Before the Revolutionary War, evangelical colonists were the primary advocates for the opposition to slavery and the slave trade, doing so on the basis of humanitarian ethics.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Still, others such as James Oglethorpe, the founder of the colony of Georgia, also retained political motivations for the removal of slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Prohibiting slavery through the 1735 Georgia Experiment in part to prevent Spanish partnership with Georgia's runaway slaves, Oglethorpe eventually revoked the act in 1750 after the Spanish's defeat in the Battle of Bloody Marsh eight years prior.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] During the Revolutionary era, all states abolished the international slave trade, but South Carolina reversed its decision.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Between the Revolutionary War and 1804, laws, constitutions, or court decisions in each of the Northern states provided for the gradual or immediate abolition of slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] No Southern state adopted similar policies.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1807, Congress made the importation of slaves a crime, effective January 1, 1808, which was as soon as Article I, section 9 of the Constitution allowed.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] A small but dedicated group, under leaders such as William Lloyd Garrison and Frederick Douglass, agitated for abolition in the mid-19th century.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Brown became an advocate and militia leader in attempting to end slavery by force of arms.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the Civil War, immediate emancipation became a war goal for the Union in 1863 and was fully achieved in 1865.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] American abolitionism began well before the United States was founded as a nation.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1652, Rhode Island made it illegal for any person, black or white, to be "bound" longer than ten years.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The law, however, was widely ignored, and Rhode Island became involved in the slave trade in 1700.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] An early prominent example of resistance by enslaved people occurred during Bacon's Rebellion in 1676.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Occurring in Virginia, the rebellion saw European indentured servants and African people (of indentured, enslaved, and free negroes) band together against William Berkeley because of his refusal to fully remove Native American tribes in the region.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] At the time, Native Americans in the region were hosting raids against lower-class settlers encroaching on their land after the Third Powhatan War (1644–1646), which left many white and black indentured servants and slaves without a sense of protection from their government.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Led by Nathaniel Bacon, the unification that occurred between the white lower class and blacks during this rebellion was perceived as dangerous and thus was quashed with the implementation of the Virginia Slave Codes of 1705.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Still, this event introduced the premise that blacks and whites could work together towards the goal of self-liberation, which became increasingly prevalent as abolition gained traction within America.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first written statement against slavery in Colonial America was prepared in 1688 by members of the Religious Society of Friends.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The intention of the petition was to stop slavery within the Quaker community, where 70% of Quakers owned slaves between 1681 and 1705.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It acknowledged the universal rights of all people.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While the Quaker establishment did not take action at that time, the unusually early, clear, and forceful argument in the petition initiated the spirit that finally led to the end of slavery in the Society of Friends (1776) and in the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania (1780).
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Quaker Quarterly Meeting of Chester, Pennsylvania, made its first protest in 1711.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Within a few decades the entire slave trade was under attack, being opposed by such Quaker leaders as William Burling, Benjamin Lay, Ralph Sandiford, William Southby, John Woolman, and Anthony Benezet.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Benezet was particularly influential, inspiring a later generation of notable anti-slavery activists, including Granville Sharp, John Wesley, Thomas Clarkson, Olaudah Equiano, Benjamin Franklin, Benjamin Rush, Absalom Jones, and Bishop Richard Allen, among others.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Samuel Sewall, a prominent Bostonian, wrote *The Selling of Joseph* (1700) in protest of the widening practice of outright slavery as opposed to indentured servitude in the colonies.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This is the earliest-recorded anti-slavery tract published in the future United States.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Slavery was banned in the colony of Georgia soon after its founding in 1733.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The colony's founder, James Edward Oglethorpe, fended off repeated attempts by South Carolina merchants and land speculators to introduce slavery into the colony.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] His motivations included tactical defense against Spanish collusion with runaway slaves, and prevention of Georgia's largely reformed criminal population from replicating South Carolina's planter class structure.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1737, Quaker abolitionist Benjamin Lay published *All Slave-Keepers That Keep the Innocent in Bondage, Apostates*, which was printed by his friend, Benjamin Franklin.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The event resulted in 25 colonists and 35 to 50 African slaves killed, as well as the implementation of the 1740 Negro Act to prevent another slave uprising.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In her book, "The Slave's Cause" by Manisha Sinha, Sinha considers the Stono Rebellion to be an important act of abolition from the perspective of the slave, recognizing their agency and subsequent humanity as cause for self-liberation.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The struggle between Georgia and South Carolina led to the first debates in Parliament over the issue of slavery, occurring between 1740 and 1742.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Rhode Island Quakers, associated with Moses Brown, were among the first in America to free slaves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Benjamin Rush was another leader, as were many Quakers.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Woolman gave up most of his business in 1756 to devote himself to campaigning against slavery along with other Quakers.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Between 1764 and 1774, seventeen enslaved African Americans appeared before the Massachusetts courts in freedom suits, spurred on the decision made in the *Somerset v.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Stewart* case, which although not applying the colonies was still received positively by American abolitionists.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Boston lawyer Benjamin Kent represented them.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Whipple*) to liberate Jenny Slew, a mixed-race woman who had been kidnapped in Massachusetts and then handled as a slave.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to historian Steven Pincus, many of the colonial legislatures worked to enact laws that would limit slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Provincial legislature of Massachusetts Bay, as noted by historian Gary B.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nash, approved a law "prohibiting the importation and purchase of slaves by any Massachusetts citizen." The Loyalist governor of Massachusetts, Thomas Hutchinson, vetoed the law, an action that prompted angered reaction from the general public.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] American abolitionists were cheered by the decision in *Somerset v Stewart* (1772), which prohibited slavery in the United Kingdom, though not in its colonies.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1774, the influential Fairfax Resolves called for an end to the "wicked, cruel and unnatural" Atlantic slave trade.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] One of the first articles advocating the emancipation of slaves and the abolition of slavery was written by Thomas Paine.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Titled "African Slavery in America", it appeared on 8 March 1775 in the *Postscript to the Pennsylvania Journal and Weekly Advertiser*.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Society for the Relief of Free Negroes Unlawfully Held in Bondage (Pennsylvania Abolition Society) was the first American abolition society, formed 14 April 1775, in Philadelphia, primarily by Quakers.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The society suspended operations during the American Revolutionary War and was reorganized in 1784, with Benjamin Franklin as its first president.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1777, the Vermont Republic became the first independent state in North America to prohibit slavery: slaves were not directly freed, but masters were required to remove slaves from Vermont.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Constitution included several provisions which accommodated slavery, although none used the word.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Passed unanimously by the Congress of the Confederation in 1787, the Northwest Ordinance forbade slavery in the Northwest Territory, a vast area (the future Ohio, Indiana, Illinois, Michigan, and Wisconsin) in which slavery had been legal, but population was sparse.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first state to begin a gradual abolition of slavery was Pennsylvania, in 1780.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] All importation of slaves was prohibited, but none were freed at first, only the slaves of masters who failed to register them with the state, along with the "future children" of enslaved mothers.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Those enslaved in Pennsylvania before the 1780 law went into effect were not freed until 1847.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Massachusetts took a much more radical position.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1780, during the Revolution, Massachusetts ratified its constitution and included within it a clause that declared all men equal.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Based upon this clause, several freedom suits were filed by enslaved African Americans living in Massachusetts.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1783, its Supreme Court, in the case of *Commonwealth v.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nathaniel Jennison*, reaffirmed the case of *Brom and Bett v.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Ashley*, which held that even slaves were people who had a constitutional right to liberty.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This gave freedom to slaves, effectively abolishing slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] States with a greater economic interest in slaves, such as New York and New Jersey, passed gradual emancipation laws.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While some of these laws were gradual, these states enacted the first abolition laws in the entire "New World".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the State of New York, the enslaved population was transformed into indentured servants before being granted full emancipation in 1827.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In other states, abolitionist legislation provided freedom only for the children of the enslaved.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In New Jersey, slavery was not fully prohibited until the passage of the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] All of the other states north of Maryland began gradual abolition of slavery between 1781 and 1804, based on the Pennsylvania model and by 1804, all the Northern states had passed laws to gradually or immediately abolish it.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some slaves continued in involuntary, unpaid "indentured servitude" for two more decades, and others were moved south and sold to new owners in slave states.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some individual slaveholders, particularly in the upper South, freed slaves, sometimes in their wills.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Many noted they had been moved by the revolutionary ideals of the equality of men.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The number of free blacks as a proportion of the black population in the upper South increased from less than 1 percent to nearly 10 percent between 1790 and 1810 as a result of these actions.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some slave owners, concerned about the increase in free blacks, which they viewed as destabilizing, freed slaves on condition that they emigrate to Africa.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] All U.S. states abolished the transatlantic slave trade by 1798.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] South Carolina, which had abolished the slave trade in 1787, reversed that decision in 1803.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the American South, freedom suits were rejected by the courts, which held that the rights in the state constitutions did not apply to African Americans.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The institution of slavery remained solid in the South, and that region's customs and social beliefs evolved into a strident defense of slavery in response to the rise of a growing anti-slavery stance in the North.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1835 alone, abolitionists mailed over a million pieces of anti-slavery literature to the South, giving rise to the gag rules in Congress, after the theft of mail from the Charleston, South Carolina, post office, and much back-and-forth about whether postmasters were required to deliver this mail.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to the Postmaster General, they were not.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Under the Constitution, the importation of enslaved persons could not be prohibited until 1808 (20 years).
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] As the end of the 20 years approached, an Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves sailed through Congress with little opposition.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] President Jefferson signed it, and it went effect on January 1, 1808.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1820, the Act to Protect the Commerce of the United States and Punish the Crime of Piracy was passed.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This law made importing slaves into the United States a death penalty offense.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1830, most Americans were, at least in principle, opposed to slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, opponents of slavery deliberated on how to end the institution, as well as what would become of the slaves once they were free.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the 1830s there was a progressive shift in thinking in the North.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Mainstream opinion changed from gradual emancipation and resettlement of freed blacks in Africa, sometimes a condition of their manumission, to immediatism: freeing all the slaves immediately and sorting out the problems later.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This change was in many cases sudden, a consequence of the individual's coming in direct contact with the horrors of American slavery, or hearing of them from a credible source.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The American beginning of abolitionism as a political movement is usually dated from 1 January 1831, when Wm.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lloyd Garrison (as he always signed himself) published the first issue of his new weekly newspaper, *The Liberator* (1831), which appeared without interruption until slavery in the United States was abolished in 1865, when it closed.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists included those who joined the American Anti-Slavery Society or its auxiliary groups in the 1830s and 1840s, as the movement fragmented.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The fragmented anti-slavery movement included groups such as the Liberty Party; the American and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society; the American Missionary Association; and the Church Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Historians traditionally distinguish between moderate anti-slavery reformers or gradualists, who concentrated on stopping the spread of slavery, and radical abolitionists or immediatists, whose demands for unconditional emancipation often merged with a concern for Black civil rights.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nearly all Northern politicians, such as Abraham Lincoln, rejected the "immediate emancipation" called for by the abolitionists, seeing it as "extreme".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Indeed, many Northern leaders, including Lincoln, Stephen Douglas (the Democratic nominee in 1860), John C.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Frémont (the Republican nominee in 1856), and Ulysses S.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Grant married into slave-owning Southern families without any moral qualms.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Anti-slavery as a principle was far more than just the wish to prevent the expansion of slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] After 1840, abolitionists rejected this because it let sin continue to exist; they demanded that slavery end everywhere, immediately and completely.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Brown was the only abolitionist to have actually planned a violent insurrection, though David Walker promoted the idea.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The abolitionist movement was strengthened by the activities of free African Americans, especially in the Black church, who argued that the old Biblical justifications for slavery contradicted the New Testament.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] African-American activists and their writings were rarely heard outside the Black community.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, they were tremendously influential on a few sympathetic white people, most prominently the first white activist to reach prominence, Wm.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lloyd Garrison, who was its most effective propagandist.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Garrison's efforts to recruit eloquent spokesmen led to the discovery of ex-slave Frederick Douglass, who eventually became a prominent activist in his own right.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Eventually, Douglass would publish his own widely distributed abolitionist newspaper, *North Star*.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the early 1850s, the American abolitionist movement split into two camps over the question of whether the United States Constitution did or did not protect slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This issue arose in the late 1840s after the publication of *The Unconstitutionality of Slavery* by Lysander Spooner.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Garrisonians, led by Garrison and Wendell Phillips, publicly burned copies of the Constitution, called it a pact with slavery, and demanded its abolition and replacement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Another camp, led by Lysander Spooner, Gerrit Smith, and eventually Douglass, considered the Constitution to be an anti-slavery document.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Using an argument based upon Natural Law and a form of social contract theory, they said that slavery fell outside the Constitution's scope of legitimate authority and therefore should be abolished.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Another split in the abolitionist movement was along class lines.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The artisan republicanism of Robert Dale Owen and Frances Wright stood in stark contrast to the politics of prominent elite abolitionists such as industrialist Arthur Tappan and his evangelist brother Lewis.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While the former pair opposed slavery on a basis of solidarity of "wage slaves" with "chattel slaves", the Whiggish Tappans strongly rejected this view, opposing the characterization of Northern workers as "slaves" in any sense.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Many American abolitionists took an active role in opposing slavery by supporting the Underground Railroad.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This was made illegal by the federal Fugitive Slave Law of 1850, arguably the most hated and most openly evaded federal legislation in the nation's history.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nevertheless, participants like Harriet Tubman, Henry Highland Garnet, Alexander Crummell, Amos Noë Freeman, and others continued with their work.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists were particularly active in Ohio, where some worked directly in the Underground Railroad.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Since only the Ohio River separated free Ohio from slave Kentucky, it was a popular destination for fugitive slaves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Supporters helped them there, in many cases to cross Lake Erie by boat, into Canada.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Western Reserve area of northeast Ohio was "probably the most intensely antislavery section of the country." The Oberlin-Wellington Rescue got national publicity.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionist John Brown grew up in Hudson, Ohio.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the South, members of the abolitionist movement or other people opposing slavery were often targets of lynch mob violence before the American Civil War.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] His fellow Duffield Street residents Thomas and Harriet Truesdell were leading members of the abolitionist movement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Truesdell was a founding member of the Providence Anti-slavery Society before moving to Brooklyn in 1838.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Harriet Truesdell was also very active in the movement, organizing an anti-slavery convention in Pennsylvania Hall (Philadelphia).
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Another prominent Brooklyn-based abolitionist was Rev.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Joshua Leavitt, trained as a lawyer at Yale, who stopped practicing law in order to attend Yale Divinity School, and subsequently edited the abolitionist newspaper *The Emancipator* and campaigned against slavery, as well as advocating other social reforms.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1841, Leavitt published *The Financial Power of Slavery*, which argued that the South was draining the national economy due to its reliance on enslaved workers.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2007, Duffield Street was given the name Abolitionist Place, and the Truesdells' home at 227 Duffield received landmark status in 2021.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This was a direct result of the Union victory in the American Civil War.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The central issue of the war was slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the North, most opponents of slavery supported other modernizing reform movements such as the temperance movement, public schooling, and prison- and asylum-building.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] They were split on the issue of women's activism and their political role, and this contributed to a major rift in the Society.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1839, brothers Arthur Tappan and Lewis Tappan left the Society and formed the American and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society, which did not admit women.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Other members of the Society, including Charles Turner Torrey, Amos Phelps, Henry Stanton, and Alanson St.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Clair, in addition to disagreeing with Garrison on the women's issue, urged taking a much more activist approach to abolitionism and consequently challenged Garrison's leadership at the Society's annual meeting in January 1839.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] When the challenge was beaten back, they left and founded the New Organization, which adopted a more activist approach to freeing slaves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Soon after, in 1840, they formed the Liberty Party, which had as its sole platform the abolition of slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By the end of 1840, Garrison himself announced the formation of a third new organization, the Friends of Universal Reform, with sponsors and founding members including prominent reformers Maria Chapman, Abby Kelley Foster, Oliver Johnson, and Bronson Alcott (father of Louisa May Alcott).
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists such as William Lloyd Garrison repeatedly condemned slavery for contradicting the principles of freedom and equality on which the country was founded.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The most influential abolitionist publication was *Uncle Tom's Cabin* (1852), the best-selling novel by Harriet Beecher Stowe, who had attended the anti-slavery debates at Lane, of which her father, Lyman Beecher, was the president.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Outraged by the Fugitive Slave Law of 1850 (which made the escape narrative part of everyday news), Stowe emphasized the horrors that abolitionists had long claimed about slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Her depiction of the evil slave owner Simon Legree, a transplanted Yankee who kills the Christ-like Uncle Tom, outraged the North, helped sway British public opinion against the South, and inflamed Southern slave owners who tried to refute it by showing that some slave owners were humanitarian.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It inspired numerous anti-Tom, pro-slavery novels, several written and published by women.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to a book reviewer, "Next to *Uncle Tom's Cabin* (1852), Hinton Helper's critique of slavery and the Southern class system, *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857), was arguably the most important antislavery book of the 1850s." According to historian George M.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Two diametrically opposed anti-slavery positions emerged regarding the United States Constitution.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Garrisonians emphasized that the document permitted and protected slavery and was therefore "an agreement with hell" that had to be rejected in favor of immediate emancipation.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The mainstream anti-slavery position adopted by the new Republican party argued that the Constitution could and should be used to eventually end slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] They assumed that the Constitution gave the government no authority to abolish slavery directly.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, there were multiple tactics available to support the long-term strategy of using the Constitution as a battering ram against the peculiar institution.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] First Congress could block the admission of any new slave states.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] That would steadily move the balance of power in Congress and the Electoral College in favor of freedom.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress could abolish slavery in the District of Columbia and the territories.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress could use the Commerce Clause to end the interstate slave trade, thereby crippling the steady movement of slavery from the southeast to the southwest.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress could recognize free blacks as full citizens and insist on due process rights to protect fugitive slaves from being captured and returned to bondage.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Finally, the government could use patronage powers to promote the anti-slavery cause across the country, especially in the border states.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Pro-slavery elements considered the Republican strategy to be much more dangerous to their cause than radical abolitionism.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lincoln's election was met by secession.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Indeed, the Republican strategy mapped the "crooked path to abolition" that prevailed during the Civil War.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the 1850s, the slave trade remained legal in all 16 states of the American South.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While slavery was fading away in the cities and border states, it remained strong in plantation areas that grew cash crops such as cotton, sugar, rice, tobacco or hemp.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By the 1860 United States census, the slave population in the United States had grown to four million.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] American abolitionism, after Nat Turner's revolt ended its discussion in the South, was based in the North, and white Southerners alleged it fostered slave rebellion.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The white abolitionist movement in the North was led by social reformers, especially William Lloyd Garrison, founder of the American Anti-Slavery Society, and writers such as John Greenleaf Whittier and Harriet Beecher Stowe.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Black activists included former slaves such as Frederick Douglass, and free blacks such as the brothers Charles Henry Langston and John Mercer Langston, who helped to found the Ohio Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some abolitionists said that slavery was criminal and a sin; they also criticized slave owners for using black women as concubines and taking sexual advantage of them.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Compromise of 1850 attempted to resolve issues surrounding slavery caused by the War with Mexico and the admission to the Union of the slave Republic of Texas.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Compromise of 1850 was proposed by "The Great Compromiser" Henry Clay; support was coordinated by Senator Stephen A.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Fugitive Slave Law was a concession to the South.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists were outraged, because the new law required Northerners to help in the capture and return of runaway slaves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1854, Congress passed the Kansas–Nebraska Act, which opened those territories to slavery if the local residents voted that way.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The anti-slavery gains made in previous compromises were reversed.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] A firestorm of outrage brought together former Whigs, Know-Nothings, and former Free Soil Democrats to form a new party in 1854–56, the Republican Party.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It included a program of rapid modernization involving the government promotion of industry, railroads, banks, free homesteads, and colleges, all to the annoyance of the South.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The new party denounced the Slave Power – that is the political power of the slave owners who supposedly controlled the national government for their own benefit and to the disadvantage of the ordinary white man.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Republicans wanted to achieve the gradual extinction of slavery by market forces, because its members believed that free labor was superior to slave labor.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Southern leaders said the Republican policy of blocking the expansion of slavery into the West made them second-class citizens, and challenged their autonomy.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] With the 1860 presidential victory of Abraham Lincoln, seven Deep South states whose economy was based on cotton and slavery decided to secede and form a new nation.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The American Civil War broke out in April 1861 with the firing on Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] When Lincoln called for troops to suppress the rebellion, four more slave states seceded.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The crisis in Kansas Territory and the neighboring slave state of Missouri turned bloody during what was known as the Bleeding Kansas crisis of the 1850s.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Proslavery *border ruffians* and *Bushwhackers* fought antislavery "free-staters" and *Jayhawkers*.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Paramilitary guerrilla warfare became widespread in the area, as a prelude to the Civil War.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The violence would spread to many other places, including the Senate Chamber of the U.S.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Capitol where a Southern Democrat attacked a Northern Republican with a cane as his political allies watched.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Explorer, army veteran, and abolitionist John C.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Frémont ran as the first Republican nominee for president in 1856.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The new party crusaded on the slogan: "Free soil, free silver, free men, Frémont and victory!" Although he lost, the party showed a strong base.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It dominated in Yankee areas of New England, New York and the northern Midwest, and had a strong presence in the rest of the North.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It had almost no support in the South, where it was roundly denounced in 1856–60 as a divisive force that threatened civil war.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The newly-formed Republican Party gained quite a standing in the 1856 to 1857 election cycle in the U.S.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] House and Senate, cementing its status as the primary party for abolitionists and northerners for some time.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Without using the term "containment", the new Party in the mid-1850s proposed a system of containing slavery once it gained control of the national government.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Militant abolitionists demanded *immediate* emancipation, not a slow-acting containment.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some rejected the new party, and in turn its leaders reassured voters they were not trying to abolish slavery in the U.S. altogether, which was politically impossible, and were just working against its spread.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Brown has been called "the most controversial of all 19th-century Americans".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Whereas Garrison was a pacifist, Brown believed violence was unfortunately necessary to end slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The raid, though unsuccessful in the short term, may have helped Lincoln get elected and moved the Southern states to secede, leading to the Civil War.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some historians regard Brown as a crazed lunatic, while David S.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Reynolds hails him as the man who "killed slavery, sparked the civil war, and seeded civil rights".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] His raid in October 1859 involved a band of 22 men who seized the Federal armory at Harper's Ferry, Virginia (since 1863, West Virginia), knowing it contained tens of thousands of weapons.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown believed the South was on the verge of a gigantic slave uprising and that one spark would set it off.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown's supporters George Luther Stearns, Franklin B.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Sanborn, Thomas Wentworth Higginson, Theodore Parker, Samuel Gridley Howe, and Gerrit Smith were all abolitionists, members of the so-called Secret Six who provided financial backing for Brown's raid.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown's raid, says historian David Potter, "was meant to be of vast magnitude and to produce a revolutionary slave uprising throughout the South".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown hoped to have quickly a small army of runaway slaves, but made no provision to inform these potential runaways, although he got a little local support.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Army was dispatched to put down the raid, and Brown was quickly captured.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] He was tried for treason against the Commonwealth of Virginia, murder, and inciting a slave revolt, was found guilty of all charges, and was hanged.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] At his trial, Brown exuded a remarkable zeal and single-mindedness that played directly to Southerners' worst fears.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Under Virginia law there was a month between the sentencing and the hanging, and in those weeks Brown spoke gladly with reporters and anyone else who wanted to see him, and wrote many letters.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Few individuals did more to cause secession than John Brown, because Southerners believed he was right about an impending slave revolt.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The day of his execution, Brown prophesied, "the crimes of this guilty land will never be purged away but with blood.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The American Civil War began with the stated goal of preserving the Union, and Lincoln said repeatedly that on the topic of slavery, he was only opposed to its spread to the Western territories.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This view of the war progressively changed, one step at a time, as public sentiment evolved, until by 1865 the war was seen in the North as primarily concerned with ending slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first federal act taken against slavery during the war occurred on 16 April 1862, when Lincoln signed the District of Columbia Compensated Emancipation Act, which abolished slavery in Washington, D.C.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] A few months later, on June 19, Congress banned slavery in all federal territories, fulfilling Lincoln's 1860 campaign promise.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Meanwhile, the Union suddenly found itself dealing with a steady stream of thousands of escaped slaves, achieving freedom, or so they hoped, by crossing Union lines.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In response, Congress passed the Confiscation Acts, which essentially declared escaped slaves from the South to be confiscated war property, and thus did not have to be returned to their Confederate owners.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, effective 1 January 1863, which declared only those slaves in Confederate states to be free.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States Colored Troops began operations in 1863.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Fugitive Slave Act of 1850 was repealed in June 1864.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Eventually support for abolition was enough to pass the Thirteenth Amendment, ratified in December 1865, which abolished slavery everywhere in the United States, freeing more than 50,000 people still enslaved in Kentucky and Delaware, in 1865 the only states in which slavery still existed.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Thirteenth Amendment also abolished slavery among the Native American tribes.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The abolitionist movement began about the time of the United States' independence.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first abolition organization was the Pennsylvania Abolition Society, which first met in 1775; Benjamin Franklin was its president.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The New York Manumission Society was founded in 1785 by powerful politicians: John Jay, Alexander Hamilton, and Aaron Burr.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] There is quite a bit of confusion about when slavery was abolished in the Northern states, because "abolishing slavery" meant different things in different states.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] These included the first abolition laws in the entire New World: the Massachusetts Constitution, adopted in 1780, declared all men to have rights, making slavery unenforceable, and it disappeared through the individual actions of both masters and slaves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, what the abolition forces passed in 1799 in New York State was an Act for the *gradual* abolition of slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Slavery in New York did not officially end until 1827, and more than 70 enslaved people in New York appeared on the 1830 decennial census.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] No slaves appeared in the state's 1840 census.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] New Jersey abolished slavery in 1804, but in 1860 a dozen black people were still held as "perpetual apprentices".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the Northwest Ordinance of 1787, the Congress of the Confederation prohibited slavery in the territories northwest of the Ohio River.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] At the Constitutional Convention of 1787, slavery was the most contentious topic.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Outright prohibition of slavery was impossible, because the Southern states (Georgia, South Carolina, North Carolina, Virginia, Maryland, and Delaware) would never have agreed to it.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The only restriction on slavery that was agreed to was to allow Congress to prohibit the importation of slaves, and even that was postponed for 20 years.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By that time, all the states except South Carolina had laws abolishing or severely limiting the importation of slaves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] As he put it, this would "withdraw the citizens of the United States from all further participation in those violations of human rights...which the morality, the reputation, and the best of our country have long been eager to proscribe".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, about 1,000 slaves per year continued to be illegally brought (smuggled) into the United States; see Wanderer and Clotilda.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This was primarily via Spanish Florida and the Gulf Coast; the United States acquired Florida from Spain in 1819, effective 1821, in part as a slave-control measure: no imports coming in, and certainly no fugitives escaping into a refuge.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress declined to pass any restriction on the lucrative interstate slave trade, which expanded to replace the supply of African slaves (see Slavery in the United States#Slave trade).
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] After 1776, Quaker and Moravian advocates helped persuade numerous slaveholders in the Upper South to free their slaves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Manumissions increased for nearly two decades.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Many individual acts by slaveholders freed thousands of slaves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Slaveholders freed slaves in such numbers that the percentage of free black people in the Upper South increased from 1 to 10 percent, with most of that increase in Virginia, Maryland and Delaware.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By 1810 three-quarters of blacks in Delaware were free.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The most notable of men offering freedom was Robert Carter III of Virginia, who freed more than 450 people by "Deed of Gift", filed in 1791.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This number was more slaves than any single American had freed before or after.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Often slaveholders came to their decisions by their own struggles in the Revolution; their wills and deeds frequently cited language about the equality of men supporting the decision to set slaves free.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The era's changing economy also encouraged slaveholders to release slaves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Planters were shifting from labor-intensive tobacco to mixed-crop cultivation and needed fewer slaves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By 1860, 91.7% of the blacks in Delaware and 49.7% of those in Maryland were free.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Such early free families often formed the core of artisans, professionals, preachers, and teachers in future generations.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, this did not signal racial equality.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Though free from slavery, blacks still faced immense discrimination.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] For example, Delaware affirmed and reaffirmed black disenfranchisement several times throughout the late 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Delaware's General Assembly enacted harsh black codes throughout the 19th century that restricted travel, property ownership, expression, and socialization for African Americans.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The amendment failed and Missouri became a slave state.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to historian David Brion Davis, this may have been the first time in the world that a political leader openly attacked slavery's perceived legality in such a radical manner.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Postmaster General refused to allow the mails to carry abolition pamphlets to the South.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Northern teachers suspected of abolitionism were expelled from the South, and abolitionist literature was banned.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] One Northerner, Amos Dresser (1812–1904), in 1835 was tried in Nashville, Tennessee, for possessing anti-slavery publications, convicted, and as punishment was whipped publicly.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Southerners rejected the denials of Republicans that they were abolitionists.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] They pointed to John Brown's attempt in 1859 to start a slave uprising as proof that multiple Northern conspiracies were afoot to ignite slave rebellions.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Although some abolitionists did call for slave revolts, no evidence of any other Brown-like conspiracy has been discovered.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The North felt threatened as well, for as Eric Foner concludes, "northerners came to view slavery as the very antithesis of the good society, as well as a threat to their own fundamental values and interests".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The famous, "fiery" abolitionist Abby Kelley Foster, from Massachusetts, was considered an "ultra" abolitionist who believed in full civil rights for all black people.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] She held to the view that the freed slaves would colonize Liberia.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Parts of the anti-slavery movement became known as "Abby Kellyism".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] She recruited Susan B Anthony and Lucy Stone to the movement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Effingham Capron, a cotton and textile scion, who attended the Quaker meeting where Abby Kelley Foster and her family were members, became a prominent abolitionist at the local, state, and national levels.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The local anti-slavery society at Uxbridge, Massachusetts, had more than 25% of the town's population as members.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] McPherson in 1964 defined an abolitionist "as one who before the Civil War had agitated for the immediate, unconditional and total abolition of slavery in the United States".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He notes that many historians have used a broader definition without his emphasis on immediacy.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Thus he does not include opponents of slavery such as Abraham Lincoln or the Republican Party; they called for the immediate end to expansion of slavery before 1861.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As such, abolitionism in the United States was identified by historians as an expression of moralism, it often operated in tandem with another social reform effort, the temperance movement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slavery was also attacked, to a lesser degree, as harmful on economic grounds.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Evidence was that the South, with many enslaved African Americans on plantations, was definitely poorer than the North, which had few.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Historians and scholars have largely overlooked the work of black abolitionists; instead, they have focused on only a few black abolitionists, such as Frederick Douglass.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Yet lesser-known black abolitionists, such as Martin Delany and James Monroe Whitfield, also played an undeniably large role in shaping the movement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionists had the distinct problem of having to confront an often-hostile American public, while still acknowledging their nationality and struggle.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As a result, many black abolitionists "intentionally adopted aspects of British, New England, and Midwestern cultures".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Furthermore, much of abolitionist rhetoric, and black abolitionist rhetoric in particular, were influenced by the Puritan preaching heritage.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Frederick Douglass was a notable black abolitionist, who significantly contributed to the transnational abolitionist movement through his lecture tours of the United Kingdom from 1845 to 1847.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In particular, he had a connection with Daniel O'Connell: Both O'Connell and Douglass strongly opposed slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] On 4 October 1845, the British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society gave Douglass a Bible bound in gold.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] African Americans, with Douglass being a key example, were involving themselves in US foreign relations and influencing British anti-slavery rhetoric.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Douglass was best known for his speeches, and he completed 280 lectures across the UK and Ireland in the 19 months that he was there.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric discussed relationships between power, race, and the popular imagination, showing the complexities of the morality and representation of the abolitionist debate.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Douglass and other black nationalists capitalised on pre-existing political and ideological debates among the UK to reassert the need for abolitionism.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In general, Black female abolitionists had separate motives and rhetorical strategies than White female abolitionists.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were often middle class and members of literary societies; the ones to which they belonged were often made up of solely Black women.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In their activist efforts, they held themselves to high moral standards to be viewed as legitimate by others.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Sarah Mapps Douglass, a free-born Quaker who wrote articles for *The Liberator* on abolition also served as the secretary for a literary society for women in Philadelphia, where she emphasized the importance of education and morality for Black women.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women that escaped slavery would sometimes write and publish their slave narratives as a way to argue for abolition.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In opposition to male slave narratives, like Frederick Douglass's, which highlighted literacy, Black women emphasized the communities and relationships they formed as keys to their humanity and right to freedom.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were also keen to highlight their relationship to motherhood, so as to emphasize their shared traits with white women and the ways in which they too could meet traditional expectations of white women.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Harriet Jacobs's *Incidents in the Life of a Slave Girl* showcases her grandmother as the matriarch of her family, which shows how enslaved mothers are capable of nurturing like valued white women.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women also played their role in the abolitionist movement, both domestically and internationally, showing involvement in US Foreign Relations.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] One notable example was Harriet Jacobs, who produced letters in England reflecting on her experiences as a slave in the US to challenge the pro-slavery movement in the USA.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The London Emancipation Committee published her letters into a book, titled: The Deeper Wrong: Incidents in the Life of a Slave Girl, Written by Herself.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The book was not just noticed in reform journals, but in the mainstream press.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Lengthy British reviews show how the book helped abolitionists win public support in Britain.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric could be done in literary form, a way for black women to have influence in an international abolitionist movement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric was not only a transatlantic movement between Britain and the US, it also had influence in the Caribbean and South America.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The 1833 legal case Mundrucu v Barker also carried international importance in the abolitionist campaign.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In taking a stand against segregation, a black Brazilian immigrant had focused worldwide attention on racism in slaveholding US society.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Here there was division between white Philadelphians who saw black Saint Dominguan refugees as a threat to the city and country's racial order, their way of trying to justify slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This shows the connection between attitudes towards segregation and slavery helped shape black abolitionist rhetoric.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This led to domestic organisations being established by interracial communities, such as the Boston Female Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Working as Jamaican-based writers for New York newspapers between 1840 and 1851, the two black US-Jamaican brothers, Henry and George Davison provided inter-American perspectives on abolitionism.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Henry wrote letters to the National Anti-Slavery Standard.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black Americans had opportunities to write for newspapers, providing publicity and discussion of abolitionist rhetoric.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slavery was moving beyond internal US divisions, but reaching influence outside of the USA.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric was not simply an African-American activity, but involved South American and Caribbean individuals too, showing an international movement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Angelina and Sarah Grimké were the first female anti-slavery agents, and played a variety of roles in the abolitionist movement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Though born in the South, the Grimké sisters became disillusioned with slavery and moved North to get away from it.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Perhaps because of their birthplace, the Grimké sisters' critiques carried particular weight and specificity.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Angelina Grimké spoke of her thrill at seeing white men do manual labor of any kind.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Their perspectives as native Southerners as well as women, brought a new important point of view to the abolitionist movement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1836, they moved to New York and began work for the Anti-Slavery Society, where they met and were impressed by William Lloyd Garrison.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The sisters wrote many pamphlets (Angelina's "Appeal to the Christian Women of the South" was the only appeal directly to Southern women to defy slavery laws) and played leadership roles at the first Anti-Slavery Convention of American Women in 1837.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Grimkés later made a notable speaking tour around the north, which culminated in Angelina's February 1838 address to a Committee of the Legislature of Massachusetts.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Lucretia Mott was also active in the abolitionist movement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Though well known for her women's suffrage advocacy, Mott also played an important role in the abolitionist movement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] During four decades, she delivered sermons about abolitionism, women's rights, and a host of other issues.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Mott acknowledged her Quaker beliefs' determinative role in affecting her abolitionist sentiment.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abby Kelley Foster, with a strong Quaker heritage, helped lead Susan B.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Anthony and Lucy Stone into the abolition movement, and encouraged them to take on a role in political activism.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] the first National Women's Rights Convention, held in Worcester, Massachusetts, in 1850.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (The better-known Seneca Falls Convention, held in 1848, was not national).
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She was an "ultra" abolitionist who believed in immediate and complete civil rights for all slaves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Since 1841, however, she had resigned from the Quakers over disputes about not allowing anti-slavery speakers in meeting houses (including the Uxbridge monthly meeting where she had attended with her family), and the group disowned her.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abby Kelley became a leading speaker and the leading fundraiser for the American Anti-slavery Society.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Radical abolitionism became known as "Abby Kelleyism".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Other leaders in the abolitionist movement were Lydia Maria Child, Elizabeth Cady Stanton, Susan B.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Anthony, Harriet Tubman, and Sojourner Truth.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But even beyond these well-known women, abolitionism maintained impressive support from white middle-class and some black women.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It was these women who performed many of the logistical, day-to-day tasks that made the movement successful.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They raised money, wrote and distributed propaganda pieces, drafted and signed petitions, and lobbied the legislatures.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Though abolitionism sowed the seeds of the women's rights movement, most women became involved in abolitionism because of a gendered religious worldview, and the idea that they had feminine, moral responsibilities.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, in the winter of 1831–1832, women sent three petitions to the Virginia legislature, advocating emancipation of the state's slave population.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The only precedent for such action was Catharine Beecher's organization of a petition protesting the Cherokee removal.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Virginia petitions, while the first of their kind, were by no means the last.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Similar backing increased leading up to the Civil War.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Even as women played crucial roles in abolitionism, the movement simultaneously helped stimulate women's-rights efforts.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A full 10 years before the Seneca Falls Convention, the Grimké sisters were travelling and lecturing about their experiences with slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As Gerda Lerner says, the Grimkés understood their actions' great impact.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "In working for the liberation of the slave," Lerner writes, "Sarah and Angelina Grimké found the key to their own liberation.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] And the consciousness of the significance of their actions was clearly before them.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Women gained important experiences in public speaking and organizing that stood them in good stead going forward.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Grimké sisters' public speaking played a critical part in legitimizing women's place in the public sphere.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Some Christian women created cent societies to benefit abolition movements, where many women in a church would each pledge to donate one cent a week to help abolitionist causes.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Even though women were not allowed full access to political and religious spaces, they still played a big role in the abolitionist movement through both public activism and behind-the-scenes activism.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As historian Julie Roy Jeffrey explains, a lot of women relied on their religious faith and authority to speak out against slavery and challenge male-led church systems that tried to keep them quiet.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They believed slavery went against Christian values and saw it as a deep moral wrong.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In their speeches and writing, they made it clear that true faith could not exist alongside a system that discriminated against people.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Women like Sarah Otis Ernst and Maria Child used persuasive writing, public speeches, and organizing work to fight not just slavery, but also the powerful systems that kept it going.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Ernst was a strong Garrisonian who got frustrated when mainstream abolitionists started watering down their message.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She did not like that people in the movement were trying to be more politically strategic instead of sticking to the original beliefs, like full racial equality, immediate emancipation, and refusing to work with pro-slavery systems.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] At the 1852 American and Foreign Antislavery Society convention, around two-thirds of the 2,000 people there were women.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] That says a lot about how involved women were, even though they often got written out of the story.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They could not vote, but they used writing, speeches, and journalism to influence politics and public opinion.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Their activism was real, public, and tied directly into national conversations.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But not all women approached the movement the same way.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] There were clear differences between how white and Black women operated, and sometimes those differences caused conflict.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] White women, especially ones who were more religious, focused a lot on the moral and spiritual arguments.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They used Christian values to call out slavery as a sin and tried to appeal to other white Americans by framing it as a moral crisis.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, Lydia Maria Child wrote about Christian duty and compassion to get people on board.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But that type of activism did not always connect with what Black women were facing every day.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] And even inside the abolitionist circles, Black women were still often pushed to the side.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were not always given speaking time, leadership roles, or space in published work.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Sojourner Truth had to fight just to speak at some events, and even then, people questioned her.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] White women could usually speak and be heard if they used moral language.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women had to work twice as hard just to get into the room.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They faced racism from inside the movement and also from the outside world, which made it even harder for their voices to be heard.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Richmond talks about how central Black women were to abolition, even though they have been left out of most of the history.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Women like Sojourner Truth, Maria Stewart, and Harriet Tubman struggled not only for the abolition of slavery but for gender and racial equality as well".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were not just giving speeches, they were founding antislavery groups, organizing communities, and building transatlantic networks.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were working through both racism and sexism and still finding ways to be powerful voices.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Truth's line "Ain’t I a Woman?" and Stewart saying she had to "stand for justice wherever I find it" show how they were calling out not just slavery, but the whole system that tried to silence them.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Harriet Tubman took a different route; she led people to freedom through the Underground Railroad and even worked for the Union Army.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women's abolitionism looked different from that of white women.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It was rooted in their personal experience and often more direct and action-focused.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They made sure the fight for abolition was not just about ending slavery, but also about achieving full equality and justice.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The July 1848 Seneca Falls Convention grew out of a partnership between Lucretia Mott and Elizabeth Cady Stanton that blossomed while the two worked, at first, on abolitionist issues.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Indeed, the two met at the World's Anti-Slavery Convention in the summer of 1840.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Mott brought oratorical skills and an impressive reputation as an abolitionist to the nascent women's rights movement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolitionism brought together active women and enabled them to make political and personal connections while honing communication and organizational skills.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Even Sojourner Truth, commonly associated with abolitionism, delivered her first documented public speech at the 1850 National Women's Rights Convention in Worcester.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] There, she argued for women's reform activism.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The religious component of American abolitionism was great.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It began with the Quakers, then moved to the other Protestants with the Second Great Awakening of the early 19th century.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Saying slavery was sinful made its evil easy to understand, and tended to arouse fervor for the cause.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The debate about slavery was often based on what the Bible said or did not say about it.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] John Brown, who had studied the Bible for the ministry, proclaimed that he was "an instrument of God".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Second Great Awakening of the 1820s and 1830s in religion inspired groups that undertook many types of social reform.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For some that included the immediate abolition of slavery as they considered it sinful to hold slaves as well as to tolerate slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Opposition to slavery, for example, was one of the works of piety of the Methodist Churches, which were established by John Wesley.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Abolitionist" had several meanings at the time.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The followers of William Lloyd Garrison, including Wendell Phillips and Frederick Douglass, demanded the "immediate abolition of slavery", hence the name, also called "immediatism".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A more pragmatic group of abolitionists, such as Theodore Weld and Arthur Tappan, wanted immediate action, but were willing to support a program of gradual emancipation, with a long intermediate stage.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The *True Wesleyan* a periodical founded by Orange Scott and Jotham Horton was used to disseminate abolitionist views.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Methodist and Quaker branches of Christianity played an integral part in the formulation of abolitionist ideology in the United States.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Anti-slavery men", such as John Quincy Adams, did not call slavery a sin.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They called it an evil feature of society as a whole.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They did what they could to limit slavery and end it where possible, but were not part of any abolitionist group.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, in 1841, John Quincy Adams represented the *Amistad* African slaves in the Supreme Court of the United States and argued that they should be set free.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In the last years before the war, "anti-slavery" could refer to the Northern majority, such as Abraham Lincoln, who opposed expansion of slavery or its influence, as by the Kansas–Nebraska Act or the Fugitive Slave Act.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Many Southerners called all these abolitionists, without distinguishing them from the Garrisonians.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Irish Catholics in the United States seldom challenged the role of slavery in society as it was protected at that time by the U.S.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They viewed the abolitionists as anti-Catholic and anti-Irish.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Irish Catholics were generally well received by Democrats in the South.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In contrast, most Irish Nationalists and Fenians supported the abolition of slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Daniel O'Connell, the Catholic leader of the Irish in Ireland, supported abolition in the United States.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He organized a petition in Ireland with 60,000 signatures urging the Irish of the United States to support abolition.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] John O'Mahony, a founder of the Irish Republican Brotherhood was an abolitionist and served as colonel in the 69th Infantry Regiment during the Civil War.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Irish Catholics in the United States were recent immigrants; most were poor and very few owned slaves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They had to compete with free blacks for unskilled labor jobs.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They saw abolitionism as the militant wing of evangelical anti-Catholic Protestantism.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Catholic Church in the United States had long ties in slaveholding Maryland and Louisiana.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1861, the Archbishop of New York wrote to Secretary of War Cameron: "That the Church is opposed to slavery ...
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Her doctrine on that subject is, that it is a crime to reduce men naturally free to a condition of servitude and bondage, as slaves." No American bishop supported extra-political abolition or interference with states' rights before the Civil War.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The secular Germans of the Forty-Eighter immigration were largely anti-slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Prominent Forty-Eighters included Carl Schurz and Friedrich Hecker.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] German Lutherans seldom took a position on slavery, but German Methodists were anti-slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Both Garrison's newspaper *The Liberator* and his book *Thoughts on African Colonization* (1832) arrived shortly after publication at Western Reserve College, in Hudson, Ohio, which was briefly the center of abolitionist discourse in the United States.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (John Brown grew up in Hudson.) The readers, including college president Charles Backus Storrs, found Garrison's arguments and evidence convincing.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolition versus colonization rapidly became the primary issue on the campus, to the point that Storrs complained in writing that nothing else was being discussed.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The college's chaplain and theology professor Beriah Green said that "his *Thoughts* and his paper (*The Liberator*) are worthy of the eye and the heart of every American." Green delivered in the college chapel in November and December 1832 four sermons supporting immediate abolition of slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These so offended the college's trustees, more conservative than either the students or the faculty, that Green resigned, expecting that he would be fired.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Elizur Wright, another professor, resigned soon afterwards and became the first secretary of the American Anti-Slavery Society, of which Green was the first president.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Storrs contracted tuberculosis, took a leave of absence, and died within six months.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This left the school with only one of its four professors.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Green was soon hired as the new president of the Oneida Institute.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Under the previous president, George Washington Gale, there had been a mass walkout of students; among the issues was Gale's lack of support for abolition.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He accepted the position on conditions that 1) he be allowed to preach "immediatism", immediate emancipation, and 2) that African-American students be admitted on the same terms as white students.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These were accepted, and we know the names of 16 Blacks who studied there.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Native American students, of whom we know the names of two, were openly accepted as well.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Under Green, Oneida became "a hotbed of anti-slavery activity." It was "abolitionist to the core, more so than any other American college." For Presbyterian minister and Bible professor Green, slavery was not just an evil but a sin, and abolitionism was what Christ's principles mandated.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Under him a cadre of abolitionists was trained, who then carried the abolitionist message, via lectures and sermons, throughout the North.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Many future well-known black leaders and abolitionists were students at Oneida while Green was president.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These include William Forten (son of James Forten), Alexander Crummell, Rev.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Oneida Institute did not have an incident, like that of Western Reserve, which brought national attention to it.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Its successor, Lane Seminary, in Cincinnati, did.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Lane was Oneida moved west." Leading the exodus from Oneida was a former Oneida student, and private student of Gale before that, Theodore Dwight Weld.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He greatly impressed the philanthropist brothers and abolitionists Arthur and Lewis Tappan.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They hired him to report on the movement nationally, and specifically to find a new location for their funding, since Oneida, a manual labor school, was a disappointment, according to Weld and his student followers.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] At the same time that Weld was scouting a location for a new school, the barely-functioning Lane Seminary was looking for students.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Based on Weld's recommendation, the Tappans started giving Lane the financial support they had previously given Oneida.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Weld, though on paper enrolled as a student at Lane, was de facto its head, choosing, through his recommendations to the Tappans, the president (Lyman Beecher, after Charles Grandison Finney, who became later the second president of Oberlin, turned it down), and telling the trustees whom to hire.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The group of students led by Weld constituted the first student movement in the history of the country.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He chose Lane, and they followed him there.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] When he soon left Lane for another new, struggling institution, Oberlin, they did so too, as a group.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Students, many of whom considered him the real leader of Lane, responded to Weld's announcement of the new school in Cincinnati.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Lane ended up with about 100 students, the most of any seminary in America.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] One of Weld's key contentions (and of Puritan abolition sentiment in general) was that slavery was inherently anti-family.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] While slave marriage was illegal, it happened frequently.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slave owners expected their slaves to have many children to replace their numbers; Virginia and Maryland "exported" slaves to the Deep South—they were an asset like cattle—after Congress had banned the importation of slaves in 1808.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Since slaves were property they were frequently bought and sold, ripping apart families.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In his 1839 book *American Slavery as It Is*, Weld showed just how brutal the slave trade was towards families.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] To the very family-focused Puritans, this was one of the greatest crimes of slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Weld's descriptions of families destroyed would later serve as the basis for scenes in *Uncle Tom's Cabin*, including Uncle Tom's being sold and separated from the children.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] No sooner had this disparate group of former Oneida students and others arrived at Lane, under the leadership of Weld, than they formed an anti-slavery society.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They then proceeded to hold a well-publicized series of debates on abolition versus African colonization, lasting 18 evenings, and decided that abolition was a much better solution to slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In fact no real debate took place, since no one appeared to defend colonization.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These "debates", which were well publicized, alarmed Lane's president Lyman Beecher and the school's trustees.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Adding to their alarm were the classes the students were holding in the Black community, teaching Blacks to read.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Fearing violence, since Cincinnati was strongly anti-abolitionist (see Cincinnati riots of 1829), they immediately prohibited any future such "off-the-topic" discussions and activities.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The students, again led by Weld, felt that abolitionism was so important – it was their responsibility as Christians to promote it – and they resigned *en masse*, joined by Asa Mahan, a trustee who supported the students.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] With support from the Tappans, they briefly tried to establish a new seminary, but as this did not prove a practical solution they accepted a proposal that they move as a group to the new Oberlin Collegiate Institute.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Due to its students' anti-slavery position, Oberlin soon became one of the most liberal colleges and accepted African-American students.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Along with Garrison, Northcutt and Collins were proponents of immediate abolition.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abby Kelley Foster became an "ultra abolitionist" and a follower of William Lloyd Garrison.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Anthony as well as Elizabeth Cady Stanton into the anti-slavery cause.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] After 1840, "abolition" usually referred to positions similar to Garrison's.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It was largely an ideological movement led by about 3,000 people, including free blacks and free people of color, many of whom, such as Frederick Douglass in Rochester, New York, and Robert Purvis and James Forten in Philadelphia, played prominent leadership roles.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Douglass became legally free during a two-year stay in England, as British supporters raised funds to purchase his freedom from his American owner Thomas Auld, and also helped fund his abolitionist newspapers in the United States.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolitionism had a strong religious base including Quakers, and people converted by the revivalist fervor of the Second Great Awakening, led by Charles Finney in the North, in the 1830s.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Belief in abolition contributed to the formation of Christian denominations, such as the Free Methodist Church.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Evangelical abolitionists founded some colleges, most notably Bates College in Maine and Oberlin College in Ohio.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The movement attracted such figures as Yale president Noah Porter and Harvard president Thomas Hill.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In the mid nineteenth century, American abolitionism was shaped by British ideological and organisational influences.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A key part of this exchange was the intersection of abolitionism and free trade ideology.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] British reformers such as Richard Cobden and the Anti Corn Law League inspired American abolitionists to promote free trade arguing that it was morally and economically aligned to abolition in the United States.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Leaders like Joshua Leavitt, campaigner for the Liberty Party, argued that repealing British tariffs would reduce US reliance on Southern slave grown cotton and open markets to free labour goods from the North.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Another prominent British activist was George Thompson, who toured the US several times where he delivered speeches connecting Free Trade to the American abolition cause.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Figures like Cobden and Thompson were a direct influence on the ideology of Lloyd Garrison.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Another movement called the Free-produce movement extended across the Atlantic.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This movement aimed to boycott goods produced by enslaved Africans.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The movement was connected to British activist Joseph Sturge and the idea that a free market allowed for consumer morality.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Sociologist Cecilia Walsh-Russo developed the term 'mutual brokerage' to refer to the interchange of ideas within UK-US abolitionist movements.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She refers to the interactions which allowed ideas and political strategy to co-develop, rather than suggesting one learned from the other.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Walsh-Russo cites the 1840 World Anti-Slavery Convention in London as an example of mutual brokerage.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She claims the exclusion of women as delegates, despite their presence at the events forced transatlantic abolitionist to re-assess their understanding of political participation and democracy, often leading to more progressive views in UK and US activism.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Despite exclusion from the conference women asserted their right to participate in the abolitionist cause by using informal setting such as salons to promote abolition.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] William Lloyd Garrison also engaged in Irish politics.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He communicated with key figures like Daniel O'Connell, which shaped his understanding of abolition as 'universal emancipation'.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Garrisonian abolitionists also used Ireland and the Irish as tools of comparison especially in combatting the American Colonization Society.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] However, efforts to forge direct relations between Irish Americans and African Americans largely failed.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The 1842 Address from the People of Ireland to Their Countrymen and Countrywomen in America, written by Irish abolitionists and signed by O'Connell, urged Irish Americans to support abolition and racial equality.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Garrisonians hoped this would foster diasporic responsibility among the Irish but it was rejected by most.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Irish immigrants, perhaps due to a desire to assimilate in the US, were overall not supportive of the abolitionist cause.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It is easy to overstate the support for abolitionism in the North.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A majority of white Southerners, though by no means all, supported slavery; there was a growing feeling in favor of emancipation in North Carolina, Maryland, Virginia, and Kentucky, until the panic resulting from Nat Turner's 1831 revolt put an end to it.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But only a minority in the North supported abolition, seen as an extreme, "radical" measure.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (See Radical Republicans.) Horace Greeley remarked in 1854 that he had "never been able to discover any strong, pervading, over-ruling Anti Slavery sentiment in the Free States." Free blacks were subject in the North as well as in the South to conditions almost inconceivable today (2019).
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Although the picture is neither uniform nor static, in general free blacks in the North were not citizens and could neither vote nor hold public office.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They could not give testimony in court and their word was never taken against a white man's word, as a result of which white crimes against blacks were rarely punished.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black children could not study in the public schools, even though Black taxpayers helped support them, and there were only a handful of schools for Black students, like the African Free School in New York, the Abiel Smith School in Boston, and the Watkins Academy for Negro Youth in Baltimore.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] When schools for negroes were set up in Ohio in the 1830s, the teacher of one slept in it every night "for fear whites would burn it", and at another, "a vigilance committee threatened to tar and feather [the teacher] and ride her on a rail if she did not leave".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (Oberlin Collegiate Institute was the first college that survived to admit them by policy; the Oneida Institute was a short-lived predecessor.) In wages, housing, access to services, and transportation, separate but equal or Jim Crow treatment would have been a great improvement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The proposal to create the country's first college for negros, in New Haven, Connecticut, got such strong local opposition (New Haven Excitement) that it was quickly abandoned.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Schools in which blacks and whites studied together in Canaan, New Hampshire, and Canterbury, Connecticut, were physically destroyed by mobs.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (The prosecutor was Francis Scott Key.) In Savannah, Georgia, the mayor and alderman protected an abolitionist visitor from a mob.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In the North there was far more serious violence by mobs, what the press sometimes called "mobocracy".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Lovejoy, who published an abolitionist newspaper, was killed by a mob in Illinois.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Only six months later, the large, modern, and expensive new hall which the Pennsylvania Anti-Slavery Society built in Philadelphia in 1838, was burned by a mob three days after it opened.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] There were other anti-abolitionist riots in New York (1834), Cincinnati (1829, 1836, and 1841), Norwich, Connecticut (1834), Washington, D.C.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (1835), Philadelphia (1842), and Granville, Ohio (following the Ohio State Anti-Slavery Convention, 1836), although there was also a pro-abolition riot (more precisely a pro-fugitive slave riot) in Boston in 1836 (and see Jerry Rescue).
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Between 1835 and 1838, anti-abolitionist violence "settled into a routine feature of public life in virtually all the major northern cities".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Giving to blacks the same rights that whites had, as Garrison called for, was "far outside the mainstream of opinion in the 1830s." Some opposed even allowing blacks to join abolitionist organizations.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolitionists nationwide were outraged by the murder of white abolitionist and journalist Elijah Parish Lovejoy by a proslavery mob in Alton, Illinois on 7 November 1837.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Six months later, Pennsylvania Hall, an abolitionist venue in Philadelphia, was burnt to the ground by another proslavery mob on May 17, 1838.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Both events contributed to the growing American debate over slavery and marked an increase in violence against abolitionists in the United States.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Amos Dresser, a participant in the Lane Debates, was publicly whipped in Nashville.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A gallows with a note from "Judge Lynch" was erected in front of Garrison's office.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He, along with the Tappans, was hung in effigy in Charleston, S.C.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Southern post offices burned rather than delivered abolitionist publications, in which they were supported by the national Post Office.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slave owners were angry over the attacks on what some Southerners (including the politician John C.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Calhoun) referred to as their "peculiar institution" of slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Starting in the 1830s, Southerners developed a vehement and growing ideological defense of slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slave owners claimed that slavery was not a necessary evil, or an evil of any sort; slavery was a positive good for masters and slaves alike, and it was explicitly sanctioned by God.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Biblical arguments were made in defense of slavery by religious leaders such as the Rev.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Ross and political leaders such as Jefferson Davis.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Southern Biblical interpretations contradicted those of the abolitionists; a popular one was that the curse on Noah's son Ham and his descendants in Africa justified enslaving blacks.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolitionists responded, denying that either God or the Bible endorses slavery, at least as practiced in the Antebellum South.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In the early 19th century, a variety of organizations were established that advocated relocation of black people from the United States, most prominently the American Colonization Society (ACS), founded in 1816.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The ACS enjoyed the support of prominent Southern leaders such as Henry Clay and James Monroe, who saw it as a convenient means of relocating free blacks, whom they perceived as a threat to their control over enslaved blacks.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Starting in the 1820s, the ACS and affiliated state societies assisted a few thousand free blacks to move to the newly established colonies in West Africa that were to form the Republic of Liberia.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] From 1832 onward most of the migrants were enslaved people who had been freed on the condition that they go to Liberia.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Many migrants died of local diseases, but enough survived for Liberia to declare independence in 1847.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Americo-Liberians formed a ruling elite whose treatment of the native population followed the lines of disdain for African culture they had acquired in America.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Most African Americans opposed colonization, and simply wanted to be given the rights of free citizens in the United States.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] One notable opponent of such plans was the wealthy free black abolitionist James Forten of Philadelphia.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1832, prominent white abolitionist William Lloyd Garrison published his book *Thoughts on African Colonization*, in which he attacked severely the policy of sending blacks to (not "back to") Africa, and specifically the American Colonization Society.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Colonization Society, which he had previously supported, is "a creature without heart, without brains, eyeless, unnatural, hypocritical, relentless and unjust." "Colonization", according to Garrison, was not a plan to eliminate slavery, but to protect it.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Garrison also pointed out that a majority of the colonists died of disease, and the number of free blacks actually resettled in the future Liberia was minute in comparison to the number of slaves in the United States.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The first country to fully outlaw slavery was France in 1315, though it was later used in its colonies.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The first country to abolish and punish slavery for indigenous people was Spain with the New Laws in 1542.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Under the actions of Toyotomi Hideyoshi, chattel slavery was abolished across Japan since 1590, though other forms of forced labor were used during World War II.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The first and only country to self-liberate from slavery was a former French colony, Haiti, as a result of the Revolution of 1791–1804.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The British abolitionist movement began in the late 18th century, and the 1772 Somersett case established that slavery did not exist in English law.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In 1807, the slave trade was made illegal throughout the British Empire, though existing slaves in British colonies were not liberated until the Slavery Abolition Act 1833.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In the United States, Pennsylvania and Vermont were the first states to abolish slavery, Vermont in 1777 and Pennsylvania in 1780 (Vermont did not join the Union until 1791).
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] By 1804, the rest of the northern states had abolished slavery, but it remained legal in southern states.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] By 1808, the United States outlawed the importation of slaves and in 1865 outlawed slavery except as a punishment.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In Eastern Europe, groups organized to abolish the enslavement of the Roma in Wallachia and Moldavia between 1843 and 1855, and to emancipate the serfs in Russia in 1861.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The United States would pass the 13th Amendment in December 1865 after having just fought a bloody Civil War, ending slavery "except as a punishment for crime".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In 1888, Brazil became the last country in the Americas to outlaw slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] As the Empire of Japan annexed Asian countries, from the late 19th century onwards, archaic institutions including slavery were abolished in those countries.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In 1948, slavery was declared illegal in the United Nations' Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] By this time, the Arab world was the only region in the world where institutional chattel slavery was still legal.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Slavery in Saudi Arabia, slavery in Yemen and slavery in Dubai were abolished in 1962–1963, with slavery in Oman following in 1970.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Mauritania is the latest country to officially abolish slavery, with a presidential decree in 1981.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Today, child and adult slavery and forced labor are illegal in almost all countries, as well as being against international law, but human trafficking for labor and for sexual slavery continues to affect tens of millions of adults and children.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Balthild of Chelles, herself a former slave, queen consort of Neustria and Burgundy by marriage to Clovis II, became regent in 657 since the king, her son Chlothar III, was only five years old.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] At some unknown date during her rule, she abolished the trade of slaves, although not slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Moreover, her (and contemporaneous Saint Eligius') favorite charity was to buy and free slaves, especially children.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Slavery started to dwindle and would be superseded by serfdom.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In 1315, Louis X, king of France, published a decree proclaiming that "France signifies freedom" and that any slave setting foot on French soil should be freed.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] This prompted subsequent governments to circumscribe slavery in the overseas colonies.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Some cases of African slaves freed by setting foot on French soil were recorded such as the example of a Norman slave merchant who tried to sell slaves in Bordeaux in 1571.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] He was arrested and his slaves were freed according to a declaration of the Parlement of Guyenne which stated that slavery was intolerable in France, although it is a misconception that there were 'no slaves in France'; thousands of African slaves were present in France during the 18th century.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Born into slavery in Saint Domingue, Thomas-Alexandre Dumas became free when his father brought him to France in 1776.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] As in other New World colonies, the French relied on the Atlantic slave trade for labor for their sugar cane plantations in their Caribbean colonies; the French West Indies.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In addition, French colonists in *Louisiane* in North America held slaves, particularly in the South around New Orleans, where they established sugarcane plantations.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Louis XIV's *Code Noir* regulated the slave trade and institution in the colonies.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] It included the right to marry, gather publicly or take Sundays off.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Although the *Code Noir* authorized and codified cruel corporal punishment against slaves under certain conditions, it forbade slave owners to torture them or to separate families.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] It also demanded enslaved Africans receive instruction in the Catholic faith, implying that Africans were human beings endowed with a soul, a fact French law did not admit until then.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] It resulted in a far higher percentage of Black people being free in 1830 (13.2% in Louisiana compared to 0.8% in Mississippi).
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] They were on average exceptionally literate, with a significant number of them owning businesses, properties, and even slaves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Other free people of colour, such as Julien Raimond, spoke out against slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The *Code Noir* also forbade interracial marriages, but it was often ignored in French colonial society and the mulattoes became an intermediate caste between whites and blacks, while in the British colonies mulattoes and blacks were considered equal and discriminated against equally.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] During the Age of Enlightenment, many philosophers wrote pamphlets against slavery and its moral and economical justifications, including Montesquieu in *The Spirit of the Laws* (1748) and Denis Diderot in the *Encyclopédie*.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In 1788, Jacques Pierre Brissot founded the Society of the Friends of the Blacks (*Société des Amis des Noirs*) to work for the abolition of slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] After the Revolution, on 4 April 1792, France granted free people of colour full citizenship.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The slave revolt, in the largest Caribbean French colony of Saint-Domingue in 1791, was the beginning of what became the Haitian Revolution led by formerly enslaved people like Georges Biassou, Toussaint L'Ouverture, and Jean-Jacques Dessalines.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The rebellion swept through the north of the colony, and with it came freedom to thousands of enslaved blacks, but also violence and death.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In 1793, French Civil Commissioners in St.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Domingue and abolitionists, Léger-Félicité Sonthonax and Étienne Polverel, issued the first emancipation proclamation of the modern world (Decree of 16 Pluviôse An II).
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The Convention sent them to safeguard the allegiance of the population to revolutionary France.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The proclamation resulted in crucial military strategy as it gradually brought most of the black troops into the French fold and kept the colony under the French flag for most of the conflict.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The connection with France lasted until blacks and free people of colour formed L'armée indigène in 1802 to resist Napoleon's Expédition de Saint-Domingue.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Victory over the French in the decisive Battle of Vertières finally led to independence and the creation of present Haiti in 1804.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The convention, the first elected Assembly of the First Republic (1792–1804), on 4 February 1794, under the leadership of Maximilien Robespierre, abolished slavery in law in France and its colonies.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Abbé Grégoire and the Society of the Friends of the Blacks were part of the abolitionist movement, which had laid important groundwork in building anti-slavery sentiment in the metropole.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The first article of the law stated that "Slavery was abolished" in the French colonies, while the second article stated that "slave-owners would be indemnified" with financial compensation for the value of their slaves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The French constitution passed in 1795 included in the declaration of the Rights of Man that slavery was abolished.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] During the French Revolutionary Wars, French slave-owners joined the counter-revolution en masse and, through the Whitehall Accord, they threatened to move the French Caribbean colonies to British control, as Great Britain still allowed slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Fearing secession from these islands, successfully lobbied by planters and concerned about revenues from the West Indies, and influenced by the slaveholder family of his wife, Napoleon Bonaparte decided to re-establish slavery after becoming First Consul.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] He promulgated the law of 20 May 1802 and sent military governors and troops to the colonies to impose it.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] On 10 May 1802, Colonel Delgrès launched a rebellion in Guadeloupe against Napoleon's representative, General Richepanse.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The rebellion was repressed, and slavery was re-established.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The news of the Law of 4 February 1794 that abolished slavery in France and its colonies and the revolution led by Colonel Delgrès sparked another wave of rebellion in Saint-Domingue.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] From 1802 Napoleon sent more than 20,000 troops to the island, two-thirds died, mostly from yellow fever.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Seeing the failure of the Saint-Domingue expedition, in 1803 Napoleon decided to sell the Louisiana Territory to the United States.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The French governments initially refused to recognize Haïti.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] It forced the nation to pay a substantial amount of reparations (which it could ill afford) for losses during the revolution and did not recognize its government until 1825.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] France was a signatory to the first multilateral treaty for the suppression of the slave trade, the Treaty for the Suppression of the African Slave Trade (1841), but the king, Louis Philippe I, declined to ratify it.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] On 27 April 1848, under the Second Republic (1848–1852), the decree-law written by Victor Schœlcher abolished slavery in the remaining colonies.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The state bought the slaves from the *colons* (white colonists; *Békés* in Creole), and then freed them.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] At about the same time, France started colonizing Africa and had gained possession of much of West Africa by 1900.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In 1905, the French abolished slavery in most of French West Africa.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The French also attempted to abolish Tuareg slavery following the Kaocen Revolt.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In the region of the Sahel, slavery has long persisted.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The abolition wasn't strictly put in place.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Several french territories kept practising slavery until 1904 as was the case in Senegal or 1894 in Soudan.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The abolition was not strictly enforced.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Passed on 10 May 2001, the Taubira law officially acknowledges slavery and the Atlantic slave trade as a crime against humanity.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] 10 May was chosen as the day dedicated to recognition of the crime of slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] James Oglethorpe was among the first to articulate the Enlightenment case against slavery, banning it in the Province of Georgia on humanitarian grounds, and arguing against it in Parliament.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Soon after Oglethorpe's death in 1785, Sharp and More united with William Wilberforce and others in forming the Clapham Sect.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The Somersett case in 1772, in which a fugitive slave was freed with the judgement that slavery did not exist under English common law, helped launch the British movement to abolish slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Though anti-slavery sentiments were widespread by the late 18th century, many colonies and emerging nations continued to use slave labor: Dutch, French, British, Spanish, and Portuguese territories in the West Indies, South America, and the Southern United States.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] After the American Revolution established the United States, many Loyalists who fled the Northern United States immigrated to the British province of Quebec, bringing an English majority population as well as many slaves, leading the province to ban the institution in 1793 (see Slavery in Canada).
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In 1787, the Society for Effecting the Abolition of the Slave Trade was formed in London.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The last known form of enforced servitude of adults (villeinage) had disappeared in England by the beginning of the 17th century.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In 1569 a court considered the case of Cartwright, who had bought a slave from Russia.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The court ruled English law could not recognize slavery, as it was never established officially.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] This ruling was overshadowed by later developments; it was upheld in 1700 by the Lord Chief Justice John Holt when he ruled that a slave became free as soon as he arrived in England.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] During the English Civil Wars of the mid-seventeenth century, sectarian radicals challenged slavery and other threats to personal freedom.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Their ideas influenced many antislavery thinkers in the eighteenth century.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In addition to English colonists importing slaves to the North American colonies, by the 18th century, traders began to import slaves from Africa, India and East Asia (where they were trading) to London and Edinburgh to work as personal servants.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Men who migrated to the North American colonies often took their East Indian slaves or servants with them, as East Indians have been documented in colonial records.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Some of the first freedom suits, court cases in the British Isles to challenge the legality of slavery, took place in Scotland in 1755 and 1769.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Each of the slaves had been baptized in Scotland and challenged the legality of slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] They set the precedent of legal procedure in British courts that would later lead to successful outcomes for the plaintiffs.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In these cases, deaths of the plaintiff and defendant, respectively, brought an end before court decisions.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] African slaves were not bought or sold in London but were brought by masters from other areas.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Together with people from other nations, especially non-Christian, Africans were considered foreigners, not able to be English subjects.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] At the time, England had no naturalization procedure.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The African slaves' legal status was unclear until 1772 and Somersett's Case, when the fugitive slave James Somersett forced a decision by the courts.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Somersett had escaped, and his master, Charles Steuart, had him captured and imprisoned on board a ship, intending to ship him to Jamaica to be resold into slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] While in London, Somersett had been baptized; three godparents issued a writ of *habeas corpus*.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] As a result, Lord Mansfield, Chief Justice of the Court of the King's Bench, had to judge whether Somersett's abduction was lawful or not under English common law.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] No legislation had ever been passed to establish slavery in England.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The case received national attention, and five advocates supported the action on behalf of Somersett.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Although the exact legal implications of the judgement are unclear when analysed by lawyers, the judgement was generally taken at the time to have determined that slavery did not exist under English common law and was thus prohibited in England.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The decision did not apply to the British overseas territories; by then, for example, the American colonies had established slavery by positive laws.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Somersett's case became a significant part of the common law of slavery in the English-speaking world and it helped launch the movement to abolish slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] After reading about Somersett's Case, Joseph Knight, an enslaved African who had been purchased by his master John Wedderburn in Jamaica and brought to Scotland, left him.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Married and with a child, he filed a freedom suit, on the grounds that he could not be held as a slave in Great Britain.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Wedderburn* (1778), Wedderburn said that Knight owed him "perpetual servitude".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The Court of Session of Scotland ruled against him, saying that chattel slavery was not recognized under the law of Scotland, and slaves could seek court protection to leave a master or avoid being forcibly removed from Scotland to be returned to slavery in the colonies.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] But at the same time, legally mandated, hereditary slavery of Scots persons in Scotland had existed from 1606 and continued until 1799, when colliers and salters were emancipated by an act of the Parliament of Great Britain (39 Geo.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Skilled workers, they were restricted to a place and could be sold with the works.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] 28) was intended to end what the act referred to as "a state of slavery and bondage", but that was ineffective, necessitating the 1799 act.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In the 1776 book *The Wealth of Nations*, Adam Smith argued for the abolition of slavery on economic grounds.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Smith pointed out that slavery incurred security, housing, and food costs that the use of free labor would not, and opined that free workers would be more productive because they would have personal economic incentives to work harder.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The death rate (and thus repurchase cost) of slaves was also high, and people are less productive when not allowed to choose the type of work they prefer, are illiterate, and are forced to live and work in miserable and unhealthy conditions.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The free labor markets and international free trade that Smith preferred would also result in different prices and allocations that Smith believed would be more efficient and productive for consumers.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Prior to the American Revolution, there were few significant initiatives in the American colonies that led to the abolitionist movement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Benjamin Kent was the lawyer who took on most of the cases of slaves suing their masters for personal illegal enslavement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] He was the first lawyer to successfully establish a slave's freedom.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In addition, Brigadier General Samuel Birch created the *Book of Negroes*, to establish which slaves were free after the war.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In 1783, an anti-slavery movement began among the British public to end slavery throughout the British Empire.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] After the formation of the Committee for the Abolition of the Slave Trade in 1787, William Wilberforce led the cause of abolition through the parliamentary campaign.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Thomas Clarkson became the group's most prominent researcher, gathering vast amounts of data on the trade.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] One aspect of abolitionism during this period was the effective use of images such as the famous Josiah Wedgwood "Am I Not A Man and a Brother?" anti-slavery medallion of 1787.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Clarkson described the medallion as "promoting the cause of justice, humanity and freedom".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The 1792 Slave Trade Bill passed the House of Commons mangled and mutilated by the modifications and amendments of Pitt, it lay for years, in the House of Lords.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Biographer William Hague considers the unfinished abolition of the slave trade to be Pitt's greatest failure.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The Slave Trade Act 1807 was passed by the British Parliament on 25 March 1807, making the slave trade illegal throughout the British Empire.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Britain used its influence to coerce other countries to agree to treaties to end their slave trade and allow the Royal Navy to seize their slave ships.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Britain enforced the abolition of the trade because the act made trading slaves within British territories illegal.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] However, the act repealed the Amelioration Act 1798 which attempted to improve conditions for slaves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The end of the slave trade did not end slavery as a whole.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In the 1820s, the abolitionist movement revived to campaign against the institution of slavery itself.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In 1823 the first Anti-Slavery Society, the Society for the Mitigation and Gradual Abolition of Slavery Throughout the British Dominions, was founded.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Many of its members had previously campaigned against the slave trade.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] On 28 August 1833, the Slavery Abolition Act 1833 was passed.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] It purchased the slaves from their masters and paved the way for the abolition of slavery throughout the British Empire by 1838, after which the first Anti-Slavery Society was wound up.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In 1839, the British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society was formed by Joseph Sturge, which attempted to outlaw slavery worldwide and also to pressure the government to help enforce the suppression of the slave trade by declaring slave traders to be pirates.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The world's oldest international human rights organization, it continues today as Anti-Slavery International.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Thomas Clarkson was the key speaker at the World Anti-Slavery Convention it held in London in 1840.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In the principalities of Wallachia and Moldavia, the government held slavery of the Roma (often referred to as Gypsies) as legal at the beginning of the 19th century.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The progressive pro-European and anti-Ottoman movement, which gradually gained power in the two principalities, also worked to abolish that slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Between 1843 and 1855, the principalities emancipated all of the 250,000 enslaved Roma people.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Bartolomé de las Casas was a 16th-century Spanish Dominican priest, the first resident Bishop of Chiapas (Central America, today Mexico).
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] As a settler in the New World he witnessed and opposed the poor treatment and virtual slavery of the Native Americans by the Spanish colonists, under the encomienda system.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] He advocated before King Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor on behalf of rights for the natives.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Las Casas for 20 years worked to get African slaves imported to replace natives; African slavery was everywhere and no one talked of ridding the New World of it, though France had abolished slavery in France itself and there was talk in other countries about doing the same.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] However, Las Casas had a late change of heart, and became an advocate for the Africans in the colonies.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] His book, *A Short Account of the Destruction of the Indies*, contributed to Spanish passage of colonial legislation known as the New Laws of 1542, which abolished native slavery for the first time in European colonial history.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] It ultimately led to the Valladolid debate, the first European debate about the rights of colonized people.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] During the early 19th century, slavery expanded rapidly in Brazil, Cuba, and the United States, while at the same time the new republics of mainland Spanish America became committed to the gradual abolition of slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] During the Spanish American wars for independence (1810–1826), slavery was abolished in most of Latin America, though it continued until 1873 in Puerto Rico, 1886 in Cuba, and 1888 in Brazil (where it was abolished by the *Lei Áurea*, the "Golden Law").
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Chile declared freedom of wombs in 1811, followed by the United Provinces of the River Plate in 1813, Colombia and Venezuela in 1821, but without abolishing slavery completely.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] While Chile abolished slavery in 1823, Argentina did so with the signing of the Argentine Constitution of 1853.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Slavery was abolished in Uruguay during the *Guerra Grande*, by both the government of Fructuoso Rivera and the government in exile of Manuel Oribe.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Throughout the growth of slavery in the American South, Nova Scotia became a destination for black refugees leaving Southern Colonies and United States.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] While many blacks who arrived in Nova Scotia during the American Revolution were free, others were not.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Black slaves also arrived in Nova Scotia as the property of White American Loyalists.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In 1772, prior to the American Revolution, Britain determined that slavery could not exist in the British Isles followed by the *Knight v.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Wedderburn* decision in Scotland in 1778.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] This decision, in turn, influenced the colony of Nova Scotia.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In 1788, abolitionist James Drummond MacGregor from Pictou published the first anti-slavery literature in Canada and began purchasing slaves' freedom and chastising his colleagues in the Presbyterian church who owned slaves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Led by Richard John Uniacke, in 1787, 1789 and again on 11 January 1808, the Nova Scotian legislature refused to legalize slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Two chief justices, Thomas Andrew Lumisden Strange (1790–1796) and Sampson Salter Blowers (1797–1832) were instrumental in freeing slaves from their owners in Nova Scotia.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] They were held in high regard in the colony.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] By the end of the War of 1812 and the arrival of the Black Refugees, there were few slaves left in Nova Scotia.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The Slave Trade Act 1807 outlawed the slave trade in the British Empire and the Slavery Abolition Act 1833 outlawed slavery altogether.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] With slaves escaping to New York and New England, legislation for gradual emancipation was passed in Upper Canada (1793) and Lower Canada (1803).
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In Upper Canada, the Act Against Slavery of 1793 was passed by the Assembly under the auspices of John Graves Simcoe.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] It was the first legislation against slavery in the British Empire.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Under its provisions no new slaves could be imported, slaves already in the province would remain enslaved until death, and children born to female slaves would be slaves but must be freed at the age of 25.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The last slaves in Canada gained their freedom when slavery was abolished in the entire British Empire by the Slavery Abolition Act 1833.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In his book *The Struggle For Equality*, historian James M.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] McPherson defines an abolitionist "as one who before the Civil War had agitated for the immediate, unconditional, and total abolition of slavery in the United States".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] He does not include antislavery activists such as Abraham Lincoln or the Republican Party, which called for the gradual ending of slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Benjamin Franklin, a slaveholder for much of his life, became a leading member of the Pennsylvania Society for the Abolition of Slavery, the first recognized organization for abolitionists in the United States.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Following the American Revolutionary War, Northern states abolished slavery, beginning with the 1777 Constitution of Vermont, followed by Pennsylvania's gradual emancipation act in 1780.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Other states with more of an economic interest in slaves, such as New York and New Jersey, also passed gradual emancipation laws, and by 1804, all the Northern states had abolished it, although this did not mean that already enslaved people were freed.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Some had to work without wages as "indentured servants" for two more decades, although they could no longer be sold.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The 1836–1837 campaign to end free speech in Alton, Illinois, culminated in the 7 November 1837 mob murder of abolitionist newspaper editor Elijah Parish Lovejoy, which was covered in newspapers nationwide, causing a rise in membership in abolitionist societies.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] By 1840 more than 15,000 people were members of abolitionist societies in the United States.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In the 1850s in the fifteen states constituting the American South, slavery was legally established.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] While it was fading away in the cities as well as in the border states, it remained strong in plantation areas that grew cotton for export, or sugar, tobacco, or hemp.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] According to the 1860 United States census, the slave population in the United States had grown to four million.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] American abolitionism was based in the North, although there were anti-abolitionist riots in several cities.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In the South abolitionism was illegal, and abolitionist publications, like The Liberator, could not be sent to Southern post offices.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Amos Dresser, a white alumnus of Lane Theological Seminary, was publicly whipped in Nashville, Tennessee, for possessing abolitionist publications.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In addition, laws were passed to further repress slaves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] These laws included anti-literacy laws and anti-gathering laws.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The anti-gathering laws were applied to religious gatherings of free blacks and slaves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] These laws, passed around the 1820–1850 period, were blamed in the South on Northern abolitionists.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] As one slaveowner wrote, "I can tell you.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Abolitionism in the United States became a popular expression of moralism, operating in tandem with other social reform efforts, such as the temperance movement, and much more problematically, the women's suffrage movement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The white abolitionist movement in the North was led by social reformers, especially William Lloyd Garrison (founder of the American Anti-Slavery Society) and writers Wendell Phillips, John Greenleaf Whittier, and Harriet Beecher Stowe.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Black activists included former slaves such as Frederick Douglass and free blacks such as the brothers Charles Henry Langston and John Mercer Langston, who helped found the Ohio Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Some abolitionists said that slavery was criminal and a sin; they also criticized slave owners of using black women as concubines and taking sexual advantage of them.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The Republican Party wanted to achieve the gradual extinction of slavery by market forces, because it believed that free labor was superior to slave labor.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] White Southern leaders said that the Republican policy of blocking the expansion of slavery into the territories made them second-class citizens and, as the *Dred Scott* decision held, infringed slaveholders' property rights.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] With the 1860 presidential victory of Abraham Lincoln, seven Deep South states whose economy was based on cotton and the labor of enslaved people decided to secede and form a new nation.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The American Civil War broke out in April 1861 with the Confederacy's firing on Fort Sumter, a Union fort in South Carolina.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Meanwhile, four slave states, known as the border states (Maryland, Missouri, Delaware, and Kentucky), chose to remain in the Union.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] On 16 April 1862, Abraham Lincoln signed the District of Columbia Compensated Emancipation Act, abolishing slavery in Washington D.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Meanwhile, the Union suddenly found itself dealing with a steady stream of escaped slaves from the South rushing to Union lines.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In response, Congress passed the Confiscation Acts, which essentially declared escaped slaves from the South to be confiscated war property, called contrabands, so that they would not be returned to their masters in the Confederacy.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] On 1 January 1863, Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which was an executive order of the U.S. government that changed the legal status of 3 million slaves in the Confederacy from "slave" to "henceforward ... free".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Though slaves were legally freed by the Proclamation, they became actually free by escaping to federal lines, or by advances of federal troops.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Even before the Emancipation Proclamation, many former slaves served the federal army as teamsters, cooks, laundresses, and laborers, as well as scouts, spies, and guides.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Plantation owners sometimes moved the Black people they claimed to own as far as possible out of reach of the Union army.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] By "Juneteenth" (19 June 1865, in Texas), the Union Army controlled all of the Confederacy and liberated all its slaves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The owners were never compensated; nor were freed slaves compensated by former owners.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The border states were exempt from the Emancipation Proclamation, but they too (except Delaware) began their own emancipation programs.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] As the war dragged on, both the federal government and Union states continued to take measures against slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In June 1864, the Fugitive Slave Act of 1850, which required free states to aid in returning escaped slaves to slave states, was repealed.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The state of Maryland abolished slavery on 13 October 1864.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Missouri abolished slavery on 11 January 1865.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] West Virginia, which had been admitted to the Union in 1863 as a slave state, but on the condition of gradual emancipation, fully abolished slavery on 3 February 1865.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Constitution took effect in December 1865, seven months after the end of the war, and finally ended slavery for non-criminals throughout the United States.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] It also abolished slavery among the Indian tribes, including the Alaska tribes that became part of the U.S. in 1867.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Brazil and Cuba abolished slavery in the 1880s, with Cuba ending it in 1886 and Brazil in 1888.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] While actors like Gertrudis Gómez de Avellaneda in Cuba and Adelina Charuteira in Brazil worked to end slavery, it was enslaved people themselves who worked daily to chip away at enslavers' local authority.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] These practices are regionally specific based on the legal customs of the region that enslaved people knew well from centuries of interactions with Iberian slave laws.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] A key avenue for these legal arguments was the prominence of "lo extrajudicial", a field of legal interactions adjacent to a lawsuit explained by historian Bianca Premo as consisting of out-of-court settlements, public revelations, and face-to-face encounters.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The suffering of women in slavery was a common trope consistently used in abolitionists' rhetoric on both sides of the Atlantic.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] This was especially true as it relates to the image of suffering mothers and their children.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Towards the end of the nineteenth century as slavery was coming to an end throughout the Atlantic world, images appearing in abolitionist publications routinely included images of families being torn apart and pregnant women being forced to do hard labor.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] As countries imposed "free womb laws" to soften the image of slavery and bring about gradual emancipation, for many it raised the question of the justice of women being used to carry out emancipation without benefiting from it themselves.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Speeches given on the topic at the time focused on mothers and compared them to "all other mothers", using motherhood to level the subjects and objects of their speech.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Women were also often on the forefront of the abolition movement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Authors such as Harriet Beecher Stowe (United States) and Gertrudis Gómez de Avellaneda (Brazil) used their novels to call into question the humanity of slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Women such as the Grimké Sisters, Abigail Adams, Elizabeth Cady Stanton and others used their connections to political movements to advocate for the abolition of slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Enslaved women such as Phillis Wheatley and Harriet Tubman took matters into their own hands by challenging the institution of slavery through their writing and their actions.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Enslaved women like Adelina Charuteira used their mobility as street vendors and as much access as they had to literacy to spread information about abolition between freedom-seeking people and local abolitionist networks.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] White and black opponents of slavery, who played a considerable role in the movement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] This list includes some escaped slaves, who were traditionally called abolitionists.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The first international attempt to address the abolition of slavery was the World Anti-Slavery Convention, organised by the British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society at Exeter Hall in London, on 12–23 June 1840.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] This was however an attempt made by NGOs, not by state and governments.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In the late 19th century, the issue was addressed on an international level by states and governments.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The Brussels Anti-Slavery Conference 1889–90 addressed slavery on a semi-global level via the representatives of the colonial powers.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] It had concluded with the Brussels Conference Act of 1890.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The 1890 Act was revised by the Convention of Saint-Germain-en-Laye 1919.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] During the 20th century the issue of slavery was addressed by the League of Nations, which founded commissions to investigate and eradicate the institution of slavery and slave trade worldwide.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The Temporary Slavery Commission (TSC), which was founded in 1924, conducted a global investigation and filed a report, and a convention was drawn up to hasten the total abolition of slavery and the slave trade.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The 1926 Slavery Convention, which was founded upon the investigation of the TSC of the League of Nations, was a turning point in banning global slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In 1932, the League formed the Committee of Experts on Slavery (CES) to review the result and enforcement of the 1926 Slavery Convention, which resulted in a new international investigation under the first permanent slavery committee, the Advisory Committee of Experts on Slavery (ACE).
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The ACE conducted a major international investigation on slavery and slave trade, inspecting all the colonial empires and the territories under their control between 1934 and 1939.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Article 4 of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, adopted in 1948 by the UN General Assembly, explicitly banned slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] After World War II, chattel slavery was formally abolished by law in almost the entire world, with the exception of the Arabian Peninsula and some parts of Africa.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Chattel slavery was still legal in Saudi Arabia, in Yemen, in the Trucial States and in Oman, and slaves were supplied to the Arabian Peninsula via the Red Sea slave trade.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The United Nations 1956 Supplementary Convention on the Abolition of Slavery was convened to outlaw and ban slavery worldwide, including child slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In November 1962, Faisal of Saudi Arabia finally prohibited the owning of slaves in Saudi Arabia, followed by the abolition of slavery in Yemen in 1962, slavery in Dubai 1963 and slavery in Oman in 1970.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In December 1966, the UN General Assembly adopted the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights, which was developed from the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Article 4 of this international treaty bans slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The treaty came into force in March 1976 after it had been ratified by 35 nations.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] As of November 2003, 104 nations had ratified the treaty.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] However, illegal forced labor involves millions of people in the 21st century, 43% for sexual exploitation and 32% for economic exploitation.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Currently, the Anti-trafficking Coordination Team Initiative (ACT Team Initiative), a coordinated effort between the U.S.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Departments of Justice, Homeland Security, and Labor, addresses human trafficking.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] The International Labour Organization estimates that there are 20.9 million victims of human trafficking globally, including 5.5 million children, of which 55% are women and girls.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] In societies with large proportions of the population working in conditions of slavery or serfdom, stroke-of-the-pen laws declaring abolition can have thorough-going social, economic and political consequences.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p01] Issues of compensation/redemption, land-redistribution and citizenship can prove intractable.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] People in modern times have commemorated abolitionist movements and the abolition of slavery in different ways around the world.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] The United Nations General Assembly declared 2004 the International Year to Commemorate the Struggle against Slavery and its Abolition.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] This proclamation marked the bicentenary of the proclamation of the first modern slavery-free state, Haiti.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Numerous exhibitions, events and research programmes became associated with the initiative.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] 2007 witnessed major exhibitions in British museums and galleries to mark the anniversary of the 1807 abolition act – 1807 Commemorated 2008 marked the 201st anniversary of the Abolition of the Slave Trade in the British Empire.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] It also marked the 175th anniversary of the abolition of slavery in the British Empire.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] The Faculty of Law at the University of Ottawa held a major international conference entitled, "Routes to Freedom: Reflections on the Bicentenary of the Abolition of the Slave Trade", from 14 to 16 March 2008.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Abolitionist constitutionalism is a line of thinking which invokes the historical view of the Constitution of the United States as an abolitionist document.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] It calls for an appeal to constitutionalism and progressive constitutionalism.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] This vision is interdisciplinary and finds its roots in the anti-slavery movement in the United States of America and is largely based on the tenet that current state institutions, particularly the carceral system, is rooted in the transatlantic slave trade.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Some constitutional abolitionists critique the claim that the Constitution was pro-slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Radical abolitionist constitutionalism calls for the idea of dignity and the use of jurisprudence to address social inequalities.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Constitution was pro-slavery, the Reconstruction Amendments can be seen as a compromise for freedom, without allowing for the full abolition.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Criminal punishment was a major way that Southern states maintained the exploitation of black labor and effectively nullified the Reconstruction Amendments.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] This was done namely through Black Codes, harsh vagrancy laws, apprenticeship laws and extreme punishment for black people.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] The Reconstruction Amendments in their aim to promote citizenship and emancipation are believed by these thinkers to still be guiding principles in the fight for freedom and abolition.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] There are suggestions that a broad reading of the Thirteenth Amendment can convey an abolitionist vision of the freedom advocated for by black people in the public sphere beyond emancipation.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Section one of the Fourteenth Amendment was used by many abolitionist lawyers and activists throughout the North to advance the case against slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Proponents of abolitionist constitutionalism believe the Thirteenth and Fourteenth Amendments can be used today to extend the abolitionist logics to the various current barriers to injustices that are faced by marginalized peoples.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Just like abolitionism more generally, abolitionist constitutionalism seeks to provide a vision which will lead to the abolition of many different neoliberal state institutions, such as the prison industrial complex, the wage system, and policing.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] This is tied to a belief that white supremacy is woven into the fabric of legal state institutions.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Radical abolitionists are often marginalized.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] There is a belief that constitutionalism as a main tenet of radical abolitionism can change and appeal to the popular opinion more.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Historically, slavery abolitionists have had to use the public meaning of Constitutional terms in order in their fight against slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Constitutional abolitionists are generally in favour of incremental changes that follow the principles of the Reconstructive Amendments.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Some argue that the narrative and scholarly literature around Reconstruction Amendments is not coherent regarding their original aims.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] On 10 December 1948, the General Assembly of the United Nations adopted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Although outlawed in most countries, slavery is nonetheless practised secretly in many parts of the world.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Enslavement still takes place in the United States, Europe, and Latin America, as well as parts of Africa, the Middle East, and South Asia.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Modern slavery keeps around 50 million people from exercising their freedom.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] In Mauritania alone, estimates are that up to 600,000 men, women and children, or 20% of the population, are enslaved.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Modern-day abolitionists have emerged over the last several years, as awareness of slavery around the world has grown, with groups such as Anti-Slavery International, the American Anti-Slavery Group, International Justice Mission, and Free the Slaves working to rid the world of slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] In the United States, The Action Group to End Human Trafficking and Modern-Day Slavery is a coalition of NGOs, foundations and corporations working to develop a policy agenda for abolishing slavery and human trafficking.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Since 1997, the United States Department of Justice has, through work with the Coalition of Immokalee Workers, prosecuted six individuals in Florida on charges of slavery in the agricultural industry.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] These prosecutions have led to freedom for over 1000 enslaved workers in the tomato and orange fields of South Florida.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] This is only one example of the contemporary fight against slavery worldwide.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Slavery exists most widely in agricultural labor, apparel and sex industries, and service jobs in some regions.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] In 2000, the United States passed the Victims of Trafficking and Violence Protection Act (TVPA) "to combat trafficking in persons, especially into the sex trade, slavery, and involuntary servitude".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] The 13th amendment abolished slavery in the United States "except as a punishment for crime whereof the party shall have been duly convicted".
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] In 2018, Colorado became the first state to remove similar language in its state constitution by a legislatively referred ballot referendum.
[src:american-missionary-association/abolitionism-p02] Other states have followed suit, but implementation has relied on court rulings.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky, Lincoln was raised on the frontier.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was self-educated and became a lawyer, Illinois state legislator, and U.S. representative.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Angered by the Kansas–Nebraska Act of 1854, which opened the territories to slavery, he became a leader of the new Republican Party.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He reached a national audience in the 1858 Senate campaign debates against Stephen A.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election, becoming the first Republican president.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory prompted a majority of the slave states to begin seceding and form the Confederate States.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] A month after Lincoln assumed the presidency, Confederate forces attacked Fort Sumter, starting the Civil War.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] As a moderate Republican, Lincoln had to navigate conflicting political opinions from contentious factions during the war effort.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He closely supervised the Union's strategy and tactics, including the selection of generals and the implementation of a naval blockade of Southern ports.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He suspended the writ of *habeas corpus* in April 1861, an action that Chief Justice Roger Taney found in *Ex parte Merryman* that only Congress could do, and he averted war with Britain by defusing the *Trent* Affair.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 1, 1863, he issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared the slaves in the states "in rebellion" to be free.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 19, 1863, he delivered the Gettysburg Address, which became one of the most famous speeches in American history.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He promoted the Thirteenth Amendment to the U.S.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Constitution, which, in 1865, abolished chattel slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Following his re-election in 1864, he sought to heal the war-torn nation through Reconstruction.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] On April 14, 1865, five days after the Confederate surrender at Appomattox, Lincoln was fatally shot by John Wilkes Booth at Ford's Theatre in Washington, D.C., becoming the first U.S. president to be assassinated.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln is remembered as a martyr and a national hero for his wartime leadership and for his efforts to preserve the Union and abolish slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He is consistently ranked in both popular and scholarly polls as among the greatest presidents in American history.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky on February 12, 1809, Abraham Lincoln was raised on Sinking Spring Farm near Hodgenville, Kentucky.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] The captain was killed in a Native American raid in 1786.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] The family settled in Hardin County, Kentucky, in the early 1800s.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nancy is widely assumed to have been the daughter of Lucy Hanks.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy married on June 12, 1806, and moved to Elizabethtown, Kentucky.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] They had three children: Sarah, Abraham, and Thomas Jr., who died as an infant.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's father bought multiple farms in Kentucky but could not get clear property titles to any, losing hundreds of acres in legal disputes.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1816, the family moved to Indiana, where land titles were more reliable.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] They settled on a forested plot in Little Pigeon Creek Community.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Kentucky and Indiana, Thomas worked as a farmer, cabinetmaker, and carpenter.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] At various times, he owned farms, livestock, and town lots, appraised estates, and served on county patrols.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy were members of a Separate Baptist Church, a pious evangelical group whose members largely opposed slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Overcoming financial challenges, Thomas obtained clear title to 80 acres (32 ha) in Little Pigeon Creek Community in 1827.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] On October 5, 1818, Nancy died from milk sickness, leaving 11-year-old Sarah in charge of the household, which included her father, 9-year-old Abraham, and Nancy's 19-year-old orphan cousin, Dennis Hanks.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas married Sarah Bush Johnston, a widow with three children of her own, on December 2, 1819.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became close to his stepmother and called her "Mama".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 20, 1828, Lincoln's sister died in childbirth, devastating him.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] His formal schooling was from itinerant teachers.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] It included two short stints in Kentucky, where he learned to read, but probably not to write.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] After moving to Indiana at age seven, he attended school only sporadically, for a total of less than 12 months by age 15.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nevertheless, he was an avid reader and maintained a lifelong interest in learning.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln was a teenager his father relied heavily on him for farmwork and for supplementary income, hiring the boy out to area farmers and pocketing the money, as was the custom at the time.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] When he was somewhat older, Lincoln and some friends took a job carrying goods by flatboat to New Orleans, Louisiana, where the slave markets, according to the historian Michael Burlingame, "would leave an indelible impression on him....
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In March 1830, fearing another milk-sickness outbreak, several members of the extended Lincoln family, including Abraham, moved west to Illinois and settled in Macon County.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became increasingly distant from Thomas, in part due to his father's lack of interest in education; he would later refuse to attend his father's deathbed or funeral in 1851.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Some historians, such as Michael Burlingame, identify Lincoln's first romantic interest as Ann Rutledge, a young woman also from Kentucky whom he met when he moved to New Salem, Illinois.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lewis Gannett disputes that the evidence supports a romantic relationship between the two.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] David Herbert Donald states that "How that friendship [between Lincoln and Rutledge] developed into a romance cannot be reconstructed from the record".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rutledge died on August 25, 1835, of typhoid fever.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln took her death very hard, sinking into a serious depression and contemplating suicide.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the early 1830s, Lincoln met Mary Owens from Kentucky.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Late in 1836, Lincoln agreed to a match with Owens if she returned to New Salem.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Owens arrived that November and he courted her, but they both had second thoughts.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] On August 16, 1837, he wrote Owens a letter saying he would not blame her if she ended the relationship, and she declined to marry him.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1839, Lincoln met Mary Todd in Springfield, Illinois, and the following year they became engaged.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] She was a daughter of Robert Smith Todd, a wealthy lawyer and businessman in Lexington, Kentucky.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln initially broke off the engagement in early 1841, but the two were reconciled and married on November 4, 1842.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1844, the couple bought a house in Springfield near his law office.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] The marriage was turbulent; Mary was verbally abusive and at times physically violent towards her husband.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] The eldest, Robert Todd Lincoln, was born in 1843, and was the only child to live to maturity.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Edward Baker "Eddie" Lincoln, born in 1846, died February 1, 1850, probably of tuberculosis.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's third son, William Wallace "Willie" Lincoln, was born on December 21, 1850, and died of a fever at the White House on February 20, 1862.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] The youngest, Thomas "Tad" Lincoln, was born on April 4, 1853, and died of edema at age 18 on July 16, 1871.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln loved children, and the Lincolns were not considered to be strict with their own.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] The deaths of Eddie and Willie had profound effects on both parents.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln suffered from "melancholy", a condition now thought to be clinical depression.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1831, Lincoln's father moved the family to a new homestead in Coles County, Illinois, after which Abraham struck out on his own.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He made his home in New Salem, Illinois, for six years.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] During 1831 and 1832, Lincoln worked at a general store in New Salem.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He gained a reputation for strength and courage after winning a wrestling match with the leader of a group of ruffians known as the Clary's Grove boys.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1832, he declared his candidacy for the Illinois House of Representatives, though he interrupted his campaign to serve as a captain in the Illinois Militia during the Black Hawk War.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was elected the captain of his militia company but did not see combat.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his political campaigning, Lincoln advocated for navigational improvements on the Sangamon River.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He drew crowds as a raconteur, but he lacked name recognition, powerful friends, and money, and he lost the election.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln returned home from the war, he planned to become a blacksmith but instead purchased a New Salem general store in partnership with William Berry.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Because a license was required to sell customers alcoholic beverages, Berry obtained bartending licenses for Lincoln and himself, and in 1833 the Lincoln–Berry General Store became a tavern as well.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Burlingame wrote that Berry was "an undisciplined, hard-drinking fellow", and Lincoln "was too soft-hearted to deny anyone credit".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the economy was booming, the business struggled and went into debt, prompting Lincoln to sell his share.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served as New Salem's postmaster and later as county surveyor, but he continued his voracious reading and decided to become a lawyer.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rather than studying in the office of an established attorney, as was customary, Lincoln read law on his own, borrowing legal texts, including Blackstone's *Commentaries* and Chitty's *Pleadings*, from attorney John Todd Stuart.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He later said of his legal education that he "studied with nobody." He was bestowed an honorary degree of Doctor of Laws by Columbia University in 1861.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Lincoln's second state house campaign in 1834, as a supporter of Whig Party leader Henry Clay, he finished second among thirteen candidates running for four places.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln echoed Clay's support for the American Colonization Society, which advocated abolition in conjunction with settling freed slaves in Liberia.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Whigs also favored economic modernization in banking, tariffs to fund internal improvements such as railroads, and urbanization.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served four terms in the Illinois House of Representatives for Sangamon County.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this role, he championed construction of the Illinois and Michigan Canal.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln voted to expand suffrage beyond White landowners to all White men.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the chartering of the Illinois State Bank, and also led a successful campaign for moving the state capital from Vandalia to Springfield.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 27, 1838, Lincoln delivered an address at the Lyceum in Springfield, after the murder of the anti-slavery newspaper editor Elijah Parish Lovejoy.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this ostensibly non-partisan speech, Lincoln attacked Stephen A.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas and the Democratic Party, who the Whigs argued were supporting "mobocracy".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] His speech also attacked anti-abolitionism and racial bigotry.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was criticized in the press for a planned duel with James Shields, whom he had ridiculed in letters published under the name "Aunt Rebecca".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the duel did not take place, Burlingame noted that "the affair embarrassed Lincoln terribly".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1843, Lincoln sought the Whig nomination for Illinois's 7th district seat in the U.S.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Hardin was the winning candidate, though Lincoln convinced the party convention to limit Hardin to one term.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln not only gained the nomination in 1846, but also won the election.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] The only Whig in the Illinois delegation, he was assigned to the Committee on Post Office and Post Roads and the Committee on Expenditures in the War Department.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Giddings on a bill to abolish slavery in the District of Columbia, but dropped the bill when it failed to attract support from most other Whigs.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln spoke against the Mexican–American War (1846–1848), for which he said President James K.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk had "some strong motive ... to involve the two countries in a war, and trusting to escape scrutiny, by fixing the public gaze upon the exceeding brightness of military glory—that attractive rainbow, that rises in showers of blood".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the Wilmot Proviso, a failed 1846 proposal to ban slavery in any U.S. territory won from Mexico.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk insisted that Mexican soldiers had begun the war by "invading the territory of the State of Texas ... and shedding the blood of our citizens on our own soil".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his 1847 "spot resolutions", Lincoln rhetorically demanded that Polk tell Congress the exact "spot" where this occurred, but the Polk administration did not respond.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] His approach and rhetoric cost Lincoln political support in his district, and newspapers derisively nicknamed him "spotty Lincoln".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln had pledged in 1846 to serve only one term in the House.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the 1848 Whig National Convention, he initially supported Henry Clay and was among the leaders of the Illinois delegation backing Clay, voting for him on the early ballots.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] When it became clear that Clay could not secure the nomination, Lincoln joined other Whigs in shifting support to Zachary Taylor, who won the party's nomination and the presidency in 1848.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Taylor won, Lincoln hoped in vain to be appointed commissioner of the United States General Land Office.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] The administration offered to appoint him secretary of the Oregon Territory instead.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] This would have disrupted his legal and political career in Illinois, so he declined and resumed his law practice.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was admitted to the Illinois bar on September 9, 1836.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He moved to Springfield and began to practice law under John T.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He partnered for several years with Stephen T.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Logan and, in 1844, began his practice with William Herndon.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Springfield practice, according to Donald, Lincoln handled "virtually every kind of business that could come before a prairie lawyer".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He dealt with many transportation cases in the midst of the nation's western expansion, particularly river barge conflicts under the new railroad bridges.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1849 he received a patent for a flotation device for the movement of riverboats in shallow water and Lincoln initially favored riverboat legal interests, but he represented whoever hired him.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He represented a bridge company against a riverboat company in *Hurd v.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rock Island Bridge Company*, a landmark case involving a canal boat that sank after hitting a bridge.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] His patent was never commercialized, but it made Lincoln the only president to hold a patent.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln appeared before the Illinois Supreme Court in 411 cases.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] From 1853 to 1860, one of his largest clients was the Illinois Central Railroad, which Lincoln successfully sued to recover his legal fees.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln represented William "Duff" Armstrong in his 1858 trial for the murder of James Preston Metzker.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] The case is famous for Lincoln's use of a fact established by judicial notice to challenge the credibility of an eyewitness.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] After a witness testified to seeing the crime in the moonlight, Lincoln produced a *Farmers' Almanac* showing the Moon was at a low angle, drastically reducing visibility.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In an 1859 murder case, he defended "Peachy" Quinn Harrison, the grandson of Peter Cartwright, Lincoln's political opponent.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Harrison was charged with the murder of Greek Crafton who, according to Cartwright, said as he lay dying that he had "brought it upon myself" and that he forgave Harrison.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln angrily protested the judge's initial decision to exclude Cartwright's claim as hearsay.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln argued that the testimony involved a dying declaration and so was not subject to the hearsay rule.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Instead of holding Lincoln in contempt of court as expected, the judge, a Democrat, admitted the testimony into evidence, resulting in Harrison's acquittal.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Compromise of 1850 failed to alleviate tensions over slavery between the slave-holding South and the free North.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the slavery debate in the Nebraska and Kansas territories became particularly acrimonious, Illinois Senator Stephen A.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas proposed popular sovereignty as a compromise; the measure would allow the electorate of each territory to decide the status of slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] The legislation alarmed many Northerners, who sought to prevent the spread of slavery, but Douglas's Kansas–Nebraska Act narrowly passed Congress in May 1854.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's Peoria Speech of October 1854, in which he declared his opposition to slavery, was one of an estimated 175 speeches he delivered in the next six years on the topic of excluding slavery from the territories.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's attacks on the Kansas–Nebraska Act marked his return to political life.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nationally, the Whigs were irreparably split by the Kansas–Nebraska Act and other ineffective efforts to compromise on the slavery issue.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Reflecting on the demise of his party, Lincoln wrote in 1855, "I think I am a whig; but others say there are no whigs, and that I am an abolitionist....
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] I now do no more than oppose the *extension* of slavery." The new Republican Party was formed as a northern party dedicated to anti-slavery, drawing from the anti-slavery wing of the Whig Party and combining Free Soil, Liberty, and anti-slavery Democratic Party members.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln resisted early Republican entreaties, fearing that the new party would become a platform for extreme abolitionists.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln held out hope for rejuvenating the Whigs, though he lamented his party's growing closeness with the nativist Know Nothing movement.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1854, Lincoln was elected to the Illinois legislature, but before the term began he declined to take his seat so that he would be eligible to run in the upcoming U.S.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] At that time, senators were elected by state legislatures.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] After leading in the first six rounds of voting, Lincoln was unable to obtain a majority.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln instructed his backers to vote for Lyman Trumbull, an anti-slavery Democrat who had received few votes in the earlier ballots.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's decision to withdraw enabled his Whig supporters and Trumbull's anti-slavery Democrats to combine and defeat the mainstream Democratic candidate, Joel Aldrich Matteson.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Violent political confrontations in Kansas continued, and opposition to the Kansas–Nebraska Act remained strong throughout the North.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the 1856 elections approached, Lincoln joined the Republicans and attended the Bloomington Convention, where the Illinois Republican Party was established.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] The convention platform endorsed Congress's right to regulate slavery in the territories and backed the admission of Kansas as a free state.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln gave the final speech of the convention, calling for the preservation of the Union.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the June 1856 Republican National Convention, Lincoln received support to run as vice president, but the party put forward a ticket of John C.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Frémont and William Dayton, which Lincoln supported throughout Illinois.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Democrats nominated James Buchanan and the Know Nothings nominated Millard Fillmore.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Buchanan prevailed, while Republican William Henry Bissell won election as Governor of Illinois, and Lincoln became a leading Republican in Illinois.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Dred Scott was a slave whose master took him from a slave state to a territory that was free as a result of the Missouri Compromise.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Scott was returned to the slave state, he petitioned a federal court for his freedom.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] His petition was denied in *Dred Scott v.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Taney wrote in his opinion that the Missouri Compromise was unconstitutional because it infringed on slave owners' property rights by prohibiting them from bringing their slaves into the territories.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] While many Democrats hoped that *Dred Scott* would end the dispute over slavery in the territories, the decision sparked further outrage in the North.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln denounced it as the product of a conspiracy of Democrats to support the Slave Power.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He argued that the decision was at variance with the Declaration of Independence, which stated that "all men are created equal ... with certain unalienable rights", among them "life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1858, Douglas was up for re-election in the U.S.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Senate, and Lincoln hoped to defeat him.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the party felt that a former Whig should be nominated in 1858, and Lincoln's 1856 campaigning and support of Trumbull had earned him a favor.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] For the first time, Illinois Republicans held a convention to agree upon a Senate candidate, and Lincoln won the nomination with little opposition.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln accepted the nomination with great enthusiasm and zeal.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] The speech created a stark image of the danger of disunion.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Senate campaign featured seven debates between Lincoln and Douglas; they had an atmosphere akin to a prizefight and drew thousands.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln warned that the Slave Power was threatening the values of republicanism, and he accused Douglas of distorting Jefferson's premise that all men are created equal.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Freeport Doctrine, Douglas argued that, despite the *Dred Scott* decision, which he claimed to support, local settlers, under popular sovereignty, should be free to choose whether to allow slavery in their territory.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He accused Lincoln of having joined the abolitionists.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though the Republican legislative candidates won more popular votes, the Democrats won more seats, and the legislature re-elected Douglas.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] However, Lincoln's articulation of the issues had given him a national political presence.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the aftermath of the 1858 election, newspapers frequently mentioned Lincoln as a potential Republican presidential candidate.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] While Lincoln was popular in the Midwest, he lacked support in the Northeast and was unsure whether to seek the office.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In January 1860, Lincoln told a group of political allies that he would accept the presidential nomination if offered and, in the following months, William O.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Stoddard's *Central Illinois Gazette*, the *Chicago Press & Tribune*, and other local papers endorsed his candidacy.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In February 1860, Henry Ward Beecher invited Lincoln to address his congregation at Plymouth Church in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln agreed, but the venue shifted to Cooper Union in Manhattan.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the audience thought he appeared awkward and even ugly.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] But Lincoln demonstrated intellectual leadership, which brought him into contention for the presidency.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Journalist Noah Brooks reported, "No man ever before made such an impression on his first appeal to a New York audience".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Historian David Herbert Donald described the speech as "a superb political move for an unannounced presidential aspirant." In response to an inquiry about his ambitions, Lincoln said, "The taste *is* in my mouth a little".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 9–10, 1860, the Illinois Republican State Convention was held in Decatur.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Exploiting his embellished frontier legend of clearing land and splitting fence rails, Lincoln's supporters promoted him as "The Rail Candidate".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 18 at the Republican National Convention in Chicago, Lincoln won the nomination on the third ballot.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] A former Democrat, Hannibal Hamlin of Maine, was nominated for vice president to balance the ticket.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Throughout the 1850s, Lincoln had doubted the prospects of civil war, and his supporters rejected claims that his election would incite secession.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Douglas was selected as the candidate of the Northern Democrats, delegates from the Southern slave states elected incumbent Vice President John C.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] A group of former Whigs and Know Nothings formed the Constitutional Union Party and nominated John Bell of Tennessee.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln and Douglas competed for votes in the North, while Bell and Breckinridge found support primarily in the South.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] A nationwide militaristic Republican youth organization, the Wide Awakes, "turned it into one of the most excited elections in American history" and "triggered massive popular enthusiasm", according to the political historian Jon Grinspan.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] People of the Northern states knew the Southern states would vote against Lincoln and rallied supporters for him.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] As Douglas and the other candidates campaigned, Lincoln gave no speeches, relying on the enthusiasm of the Republican Party.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Republican speakers emphasized Lincoln's childhood poverty to demonstrate the power of "free labor", which allowed a common farm boy to work his way to the top by his own efforts.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though he did not make public appearances, many sought to visit and write to Lincoln.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the runup to the election, he took an office in the Illinois state capitol to deal with the influx of attention.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] He also hired John George Nicolay as his personal secretary, who would remain in that role during the presidency.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 6, 1860, Lincoln was elected as the first Republican president.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory was entirely due to his support in the North and West.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] No ballots were cast for him in 10 of the 15 Southern slave states.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln received 1,866,452 votes, or 39.8 percent of the total in a four-way race, carrying the free Northern states, as well as California and Oregon, and winning the electoral vote decisively.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] above the rotunda still under construction.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] following Lincoln's first inauguration portended imminent hostilities.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Lincoln's election, secessionists implemented plans to leave the Union before he took office in March 1861.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] On December 20, 1860, South Carolina adopted an ordinance of secession; by February 1, 1861, Florida, Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas had followed.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Six of these states declared themselves to be a sovereign nation, the Confederate States of America, selecting Jefferson Davis as its provisional president.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] The upper South and border states (Delaware, Maryland, Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, Kentucky, Missouri, and Arkansas) initially rejected the secessionist appeal.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] President Buchanan and President-elect Lincoln refused to recognize the Confederacy, declaring secession illegal.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 11, 1861, Lincoln gave a particularly emotional farewell address upon leaving Springfield for Washington.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and the Republicans rejected the proposed Crittenden Compromise as contrary to the party's platform of free-soil in the territories.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln said, "I will suffer death before I consent ... to any concession or compromise which looks like buying the privilege to take possession of this government to which we have a constitutional right".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln supported the Corwin Amendment to the U.S.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Constitution, which would have protected slavery in states where it already existed.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] The amendment passed Congress and was awaiting ratification by the required three-fourths of the states when Southern states began to secede.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] On March 4, 1861, in his first inaugural address, Lincoln said that, because he held "such a provision to now be implied constitutional law, I have no objection to its being made express, and irrevocable".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Due to secessionist plots, careful attention was paid to Lincoln's security and the train he took to Washington.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president-elect evaded suspected assassins in Baltimore.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] He traveled in disguise, wearing a soft felt hat instead of his customary stovepipe hat and draping an overcoat over his shoulders while hunching to conceal his height.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 23, 1861, he arrived in Washington, D.C., which was placed under military guard.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many in the opposition press criticized his secretive journey; opposition newspapers mocked Lincoln with caricatures showing him sneaking into the capital.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president ended his address with an appeal to the people of the South: "We are not enemies, but friends....
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] The mystic chords of memory, stretching from every battle-field, and patriot grave, to every living heart and hearthstone ... will yet swell the chorus of the Union, when again touched ... by the better angels of our nature".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Donald, the failure of the Peace Conference of 1861 to attract the attendance of seven of the Confederate states signaled that legislative compromise was not a practical expectation.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] In selecting his cabinet, Lincoln chose the men he found the most competent, even when they had been his opponents for the presidency.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln commented on his thought process, "We need the strongest men of the party in the Cabinet.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] We needed to hold our own people together.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] I had looked the party over and concluded that these were the very strongest men.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Then I had no right to deprive the country of their services." Doris Kearns Goodwin described the group in her 2005 biography of Lincoln as a "team of rivals".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln named his main political opponent, William H.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln made five appointments to the Supreme Court.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Noah Haynes Swayne, a prominent corporate lawyer from Ohio, replaced John McLean after the latter's death in April 1861.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Samuel Freeman Miller, who replaced Peter V.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Daniel, was an avowed abolitionist and received widespread support from Iowa politicians.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] David Davis was Lincoln's campaign manager in 1860 and had served as a judge in the Illinois court circuit where Lincoln practiced.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democrat Stephen Johnson Field, a previous California Supreme Court justice, provided geographic and political balance.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Taney, Lincoln appointed his former secretary of the treasury, Salmon P.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Chase, to replace Taney as chief justice.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln believed Chase was an able jurist who would support Reconstruction legislation and that his appointment would unite the Republican Party.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April 1861, Major Robert Anderson, commander of Fort Sumter in Charleston, South Carolina, advised that he was nearly out of food.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] After considerable deliberation, Lincoln decided to send provisions; according to Michael Burlingame, he "could not be sure that his decision would precipitate a war, though he had good reason to believe that it might".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 12, 1861, Confederate forces fired on Union troops at Fort Sumter, starting the American Civil War.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] The April 12 and 13 attack on Fort Sumter rallied the Northern public to see military action against the South as necessary to defend the nation.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 15, Lincoln called for 75,000 militiamen to recapture forts, protect Washington, and preserve the Union.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] This call forced states to choose whether to secede or to support the Union.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] North Carolina, Virginia, Tennessee, and Arkansas seceded.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the Northern states sent regiments south, on April 19 Baltimore mobs in control of the rail links attacked Union troops who were changing trains.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Local leaders' groups later burned critical rail bridges to the capital and the Army responded by arresting local Maryland officials.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln suspended the writ of *habeas corpus*, allowing arrests without formal charges.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Merryman, a Maryland officer arrested for hindering U.S. troop movements, successfully petitioned Supreme Court Chief Justice Taney to issue a writ of *habeas corpus*.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] In an opinion titled *Ex parte Merryman*, Taney, not ruling on behalf of the Supreme Court, wrote that the Constitution authorized only Congress and not the president to suspend habeas corpus.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] But Lincoln engaged in nonacquiescence and persisted with the policy of suspension in select areas.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Under various suspensions, 15,000 civilians were detained without trial; several, including the anti-war Democrat Clement L.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Vallandigham, were tried in military courts for "treasonable" actions, which was condemned as an attack on free speech.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln took executive control of the war and shaped the Union military strategy.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] He responded to the unprecedented political and military crisis as commander-in-chief by exercising unprecedented authority.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] He expanded his war powers, imposed a naval blockade on Confederate ports, disbursed funds before appropriation by Congress, suspended *habeas corpus*, and arrested and imprisoned thousands of suspected Confederate sympathizers.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gained the support of Congress and the northern public for these actions.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also had to reinforce Union sympathies in the border slave states and keep the war from becoming an international conflict.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was clear from the outset that bipartisan support was essential to success, and that any compromise alienated factions in both political parties.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Copperheads (anti-war Democrats) criticized Lincoln for refusing to compromise on slavery; the Radical Republicans, who demanded harsh treatment against secession, criticized him for moving too slowly to abolish slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] On August 6, 1861, Lincoln signed the Confiscation Act, which authorized judicial proceedings to confiscate and free slaves who were used to support the Confederates.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law had little practical effect, but it signaled political support for abolishing slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's war strategy had two priorities: ensuring that Washington was well defended and conducting an aggressive war effort for a prompt, decisive victory.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Twice a week, Lincoln met with his cabinet.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Occasionally, Lincoln's wife, Mary, prevailed on him to take a carriage ride, concerned that he was working too hard.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, Lincoln selected civilian generals from varied political and ethnic backgrounds "to secure their and their constituents' support for the war effort and ensure that the war became a national struggle".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] In January 1862, after complaints of inefficiency and profiteering in the War Department, Lincoln replaced Simon Cameron as secretary of war with Edwin Stanton.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stanton worked more often and more closely with Lincoln than did any other senior official.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Stanton's biographers Benjamin P.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Thomas and Harold Hyman, "Stanton and Lincoln virtually conducted the war together".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln saw the importance of Vicksburg for control of the Mississippi River valley and understood the necessity of defeating the enemy's army, rather than merely capturing territory.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] In directing the Union's war strategy, Lincoln valued the advice of Winfield Scott, even after his retirement as Commanding General of the United States Army.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1861 Scott proposed the Anaconda Plan, which relied on port blockades and advancing down the Mississippi to subdue the South.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] In June 1862, Lincoln made an unannounced visit to West Point, where he spent five hours consulting with Scott regarding the handling of the war.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Internationally, Lincoln wanted to forestall foreign military aid to the Confederacy.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] He relied on his combative Secretary of State William Seward while working closely with Senate Foreign Relations Committee chairman Charles Sumner.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Navy illegally intercepted a British mail ship, the *RMS Trent*, on the high seas and seized two Confederate envoys.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although the North celebrated the seizure, Britain protested vehemently, and the Trent Affair threatened war between the Americans and the British.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ended the crisis by releasing the two diplomats.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union rout at Bull Run and Winfield Scott's retirement, Lincoln appointed George B.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, McClellan created defenses for Washington that were almost impregnable: 48 forts and batteries, with 480 guns manned by 7,200 artillerists.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] He spent months planning his Virginia Peninsula Campaign.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan's slow progress and excessive precautions frustrated Lincoln.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan, in turn, blamed the failure of the campaign on Lincoln's cautiousness in having reserved troops for the capital.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1862, Lincoln removed McClellan as general-in-chief; he elevated Henry Halleck to the post and appointed John Pope as head of the new Army of Virginia.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the summer of 1862 Pope was soundly defeated at the Second Battle of Bull Run, forcing him to retreat to Washington.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Soon after, the Army of Virginia was disbanded.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite his dissatisfaction with McClellan's failure to reinforce Pope, Lincoln restored him to command of all forces around Washington, which included both the Army of the Potomac and the remains of the Army of Virginia.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's forces crossed the Potomac River into Maryland, leading to the Battle of Antietam.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] This battle, a Union victory, was among the bloodiest in American history.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] A crisis of command occurred for Lincoln when McClellan then resisted the president's demand that he pursue Lee's withdrawing army, while Don Carlos Buell likewise refused orders to move the Army of the Ohio against rebel forces in eastern Tennessee.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln replaced Buell with William Rosecrans and McClellan with Ambrose Burnside; according to Donald, this was a "shrewd" political move as they were non-partisan—unlike McClellan, a Democrat.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Against presidential advice, Burnside launched an offensive across the Rappahannock River and was defeated by Lee at Fredericksburg in December.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Facing low morale and discontent among the troops, Lincoln replaced Burnside with Joseph Hooker.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hooker endured heavy casualties at the Battle of Chancellorsville in May, then resigned in June and was replaced by George Meade.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Meade followed Lee north into Pennsylvania and defeated him in the Gettysburg campaign but then failed to effectively block Lee's orderly retreat to Virginia, despite Lincoln's demands.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant captured Vicksburg and gained control of the Mississippi River.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] In May 1863, Lincoln issued the Lieber Code, which governed wartime conduct of the Union Army, defining command responsibility for war crimes and crimes against humanity.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two Union generals had issued emancipation orders in 1861 and 1862, but Lincoln overrode both: he found that the decision to emancipate was not within the generals' power, and that it might induce loyal border states to secede.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, in June 1862, Congress passed an act banning slavery in all federal territories, which Lincoln signed.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] In July, the Confiscation Act of 1862 was enacted, allowing the seizure of slaves from those disloyal to the United States.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] On July 22, 1862, Lincoln reviewed a draft of the Emancipation Proclamation with his cabinet.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Senator Willard Saulsbury Sr. criticized the proclamation, stating that it "would light their author to dishonor through all future generations".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] By contrast, Horace Greeley, editor of the *New-York Tribune*, in his public letter, "The Prayer of Twenty Millions", implored Lincoln to embrace emancipation.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Buttressed by news of the recent Union victory at Antietam, on September 22, 1862, Lincoln issued the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, which proclaimed that, on January 1, 1863, all persons held as slaves within any state still in rebellion would be free.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] On January 1, 1863, he issued the final Emancipation Proclamation, freeing the slaves in the ten states not then under Union control, exempting areas under such control.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] With the abolition of slavery in the rebel states now a military objective, Union armies advancing south enabled thousands to escape bondage.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Proclamation was immediately denounced by Copperheads, who advocated restoring the union by allowing slavery.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was also seen as a betrayal of his promise to Southern Unionists not to tamper with slavery; Emerson Etheridge, then Clerk of the House of Representatives, joined an unsuccessful plot to give the Democrats and Southern Unionists control of the House.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a result of the Proclamation, enlisting freedmen became official policy.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] In a letter to Tennessee military governor Andrew Johnson, Lincoln wrote, "The bare sight of fifty thousand armed, and drilled black soldiers on the banks of the Mississippi would end the rebellion at once".
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gave the dedication for the Gettysburg battlefield cemetery on November 19, 1863.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] The address became the most quoted speech in American history.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Following Admiral David Farragut's capture of New Orleans in 1862, and after victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg, Lincoln proclaimed a national Thanksgiving holiday, to be celebrated on the final Thursday of November 1863.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's victories at the Battle of Shiloh and in the Vicksburg campaign impressed Lincoln.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Responding to criticism of Grant after Shiloh, Lincoln said, "I can't spare this man.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] He fights." Following Meade's failure to capture Lee's army after Gettysburg and after Grant's success at Chattanooga, Lincoln promoted Grant to commander of all Union armies.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln reacted to Union losses by mobilizing support throughout the North.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union forces targeted infrastructure—plantations, railroads, and bridges—to weaken the South's morale and fighting ability.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] While Lincoln sanctioned this approach, he emphasized the defeat of the Confederate armies over destruction for its own sake.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody Overland Campaign turned into a strategic success for the Union despite a number of setbacks.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] But the campaign was the bloodiest in American history: approximately 55,000 casualties on the Union side (including 7,600 deaths), compared to about 33,000 on the Confederate (including 4,200 deaths).
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's losses, although lower in absolute numbers, were proportionately higher (over 50%) than Grant's (about 45%).
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April, the Confederate government evacuated Richmond and Lincoln visited the conquered capital.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Amid the turmoil of military actions, on June 30, 1864, Lincoln signed into law the Yosemite Grant, which provided unprecedented federal protection for the area now known as Yosemite National Park.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and Secretary of the Treasury Salmon Chase faced a challenge in funding a wartime economy.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress quickly approved Lincoln's request to assemble an army, even increasing his proposed 400,000 soldiers to 500,000, but both Congress and Chase initially resisted raising taxes.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union defeat at the First Battle of Bull Run, which collapsed the bond market, Congress passed the Revenue Act of 1861.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] This act imposed the first U.S. federal income tax, creating a flat tax of three percent on annual incomes above $800 ($28,700 in current dollars).
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the average urban worker made approximately $600 per year, many were not required to pay income taxes.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also signed increases to the Morrill Tariff, which had become law in the final months of Buchanan's tenure.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] These tariffs raised import duties considerably and were designed both to increase revenue and to help manufacturers offset the burden of new taxes.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Throughout the war, Congress debated whether to raise additional revenue primarily by increasing tariff rates, which most strongly affected rural areas, or by increasing income taxes, which most affected wealthier individuals; the latter view proved more popular.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] The revenue measures of 1861 proved inadequate for funding the war, forcing Congress to take further action.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] In February 1862, Congress passed the Legal Tender Act, which authorized the minting of $150 million in "greenbacks"—the first banknotes issued by the U.S. government since the end of the American Revolution.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Greenbacks were not backed by gold or silver, but rather by the government's promise to honor their value.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, $450 million worth of greenbacks were in circulation.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress also passed the Revenue Act of 1862, which established an excise tax affecting nearly every commodity, as well as the first national inheritance tax.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] It also added a progressive tax structure to the federal income tax.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] To collect these taxes, Congress created the Office of the Commissioner of Internal Revenue.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite the new revenue measures, funding the war remained challenging.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] The government continued to issue greenbacks and borrow large amounts of money, and the U.S. national debt grew from $65 million in 1860 to over $2 billion in 1866.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Revenue Act of 1864 represented a compromise between those who favored a more progressive tax structure and those who favored a flat tax.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] It established a five-percent tax on incomes above $600 and a ten-percent tax on incomes above $10,000, and it raised taxes on businesses.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early 1865, Congress reduced the threshold for ten-percent taxation to incomes above $5000.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, the income tax constituted about one-fifth of the federal government's revenue, though it was intended as a temporary wartime measure.
[src:american-missionary-association/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also took action against wartime fraud, signing into law the False Claims Act of 1863.
